  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Joshua\u2019s Great Commission"
      title: "Joshua\u2019s Great Commission"
      number: 1
      content: "And [[COMMENT(0)]] after Moses, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servant, died,   <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to Joshua <smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> son of Nun,  Moses\u2019 faithful assistant, and said, <smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:1
        content: "  The book of Joshua begins with the word \u201CAnd.\u201D What
          writer uses the connective \u201CAnd\u201D to start a new production? This
          indicates the close connection between the books of Deuteronomy and Joshua.
          In the Hebrew text every book from Joshua through 2&nbsp;Kings (with the
          exception of Ruth) begins with \u201CAnd,\u201D demonstrating that the
          history of Israel is one connected narrative and inspired by one divine
          author, the Holy Spirit.      Jewish tradition states that Moses died on
          the seventh of Adar, the twelfth month of the Jewish calendar. The book
          of Joshua takes up the story right after the thirty-day mourning period
          for Moses (see  ). Leaders may die, but God\u2019s prophetic promises live
          on.      Joshua is the name Moses gave him, changing it from Hoshea to
          Joshua (), which means \u201Cis salvation,\u201D \u201Cmay  save,\u201D
          \u201Cmakes triumphant,\u201D or \u201Cis the Deliverer.\u201D        means
          \u201Ceternal,\u201D \u201Cperpetual,\u201D \u201Cto re-sprout,\u201D or
          \u201Ceternal increase.\u201D Joshua was the son of Nun. One greater than
          Joshua is Jesus, Son of the Eternal God. Joshua is introduced into the
          story as the \u201Cson of Nun.\u201D In western culture we are identified
          by our profession, by what we do or have accomplished. But in Hebrew culture,
          we are introduced in the language of sonship\u2014as a son or daughter.
          In English, we, too, use patronyms to identify persons, which is nearly
          the same as \u201Cson of.\u201D      Seventeen times in Joshua we read
          the words \u201Cspoke to Joshua\u201D or \u201Csaid.\u201D Perhaps it was
          through an audible voice, in a dream, in a vision, in a divine encounter,
          through a prophecy, through the Urim and Thummim (see  ), or by some other
          way. God has multiple ways of speaking to his servants.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CMy servant Moses is dead. Now get up! Prepare to cross the
        Jordan [[COMMENT(0)]] River, you and all the people. Lead them   into the
        land that I am giving to the Israelites. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:2
        content: "  Jordan comes from two Hebrew root words meaning \u201Cto descend\u201D
          and \u201Cto judge.\u201D      Joshua was the successor to Moses. The leadership
          of Israel was given not to one of Moses\u2019 children but to the one whom
          God chose, prepared, and anointed. Leadership is not hereditary but established
          by the call of God on one\u2019s life. God chose Joshua in part because
          of his lifetime of service to Moses and his longing to be in the presence
          of God. See  . Moses (representing the law) was not able to take God\u2019s
          people into their inheritance, but Joshua (representing Jesus) could.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Every part of the land where you march [[COMMENT(0)]] I will give
        you, as I promised Moses.   '
      comments:
      - number: 1:3
        content: "  Or \u201CEvery place you put the sole of your foot upon,\u201D
          a figure of speech for the power to conquer. To place the sole of your
          foot upon the land or upon your enemies was a metaphor for military victory.
          See  ;  .      See  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Your borders will extend from the southern desert to the northern
        mountains of Lebanon, and from the great river Euphrates in the east, to
        the Mediterranean [[COMMENT(0)]] in the west\u2014including all the land
        of the Hittites.   "
      comments:
      - number: 1:4
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Great Sea.\u201D      God mentioned the Hittites
          because they were the strongest and most warlike of the tribes, but in
          this passage, they are representative of all the seven tribes of the land.
          There were other inhabitants of the land as well\u2014seven particular
          tribes are listed in several texts, including  . The Hittites controlled
          a vast empire (with a capital far off to the north in modern Turkey) whose
          population stretched to the borderlands of Egypt (this very region that
          was now no longer under Egyptian domination).    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Joshua, no one will be able to defeat you for the rest of your life!
        I will be with you as I was with Moses, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
        and I will never fail  nor abandon you. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:5
        content: "  What an amazing promise God gave to Joshua! In the same way 
          was with Moses (think burning bush, hearing God\u2019s voice, speaking
          \u201Cmouth to mouth\u201D with God [], performing miracles, divine encounters,
          defeating enemies), so he would be with Joshua. Throughout this book, God
          repeatedly assured Joshua of his presence (see  ;  ,  ;  ;  ;  ,  ;  ; 
          ;  ;  ,  ).      Or \u201CI will not weaken you\u201D or \u201Callow you
          to be weak.\u201D At least one Jewish scholar renders it, \u201CI will
          not part from you.\u201D (See Reuven Drucker,  , Art Scroll Tanach Series,
          1988.)    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'You must be strong and brave. You will lead the people to acquire
        and apportion the land that I promised their ancestors I would give them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "You must remain very strong and courageous! [[COMMENT(0)]] Be faithful
        to obey all the teaching  that my servant Moses commanded you to follow.
        Do not deviate from him <smallcaps>.\u201D</smallcaps> to the right or to
        the left, so that you will have overwhelming success  in everything you undertake. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:7
        content: "  To be courageous means to translate your convictions into bold
          actions.      Or \u201Claw [Torah].\u201D      This phrase could mean \u201CDon\u2019t
          deviate from [the instruction of] Moses\u201D or \u201CDon\u2019t turn
          from        Or \u201Cbe prosperous,\u201D \u201Cpush forward,\u201D or
          \u201Cbreak out.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Recite this scroll of the law constantly. [[COMMENT(0)]] Contemplate
        it  day and night and be careful to follow every word it contains; then you
        will enjoy incredible prosperity and success.   '
      comments:
      - number: 1:8
        content: "  Or \u201CDon\u2019t let this book of the law depart from your
          mouth.\u201D      Or \u201Cmeditate,\u201D \u201Cponder,\u201D \u201Cimagine,\u201D
          \u201Cmutter,\u201D or \u201Ctalk to oneself.\u201D See  ;  .      Or \u201Cunderstanding.\u201D
          See  .    "
    - name: '9: Preparation to Cross Over'
      title: Preparation to Cross Over
      number: 9
      content: "I repeat, [[COMMENT(0)]] be strong and brave! Do not yield to fear
        nor be discouraged, for I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God, and
        I will be with you wherever you go!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 1:9
        content: "  Or \u201CHave I not commanded you?\u201D      God gave Joshua
          seven promises: (1) He would possess a vast territory (see vv.  ). (2)
          No one would be able to defeat him (see v.  ). (3) God would be with him
          as he was with Moses (see v.  ). (4) God would never fail him (see v. 
          ). (5) God would never abandon him (see v.  ). (6) He would enjoy prosperity
          and success (see v.  ). (7) God would be with him wherever he went (see
          v.  ). Remember, what God promised Joshua, he also promises you, for all
          that was promised to this Joshua is fulfilled in the better Joshua (Jesus)
          in whom we are included for receiving all of God\u2019s promises as yes
          and amen.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Joshua ordered the leaders of the people: '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CGo through the camp and instruct the people, \u2018Pack your
        bags; [[COMMENT(0)]] for within three days you will cross the Jordan to conquer
        and occupy the land that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God is giving
        you to possess.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 1:11
        content: "  Or \u201CPrepare supplies\u201D or \u201CGather what you need.\u201D     
          Many scholars conclude that Joshua did not give this command until after
          the spies he sent out in ch.    had returned.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Then Joshua addressed the Reubenites, the Gadites, and the half-tribe
        of Manasseh: [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:12
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "\u201CRemember the words that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servant Moses commanded you: \u2018<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God
        is giving you this land on the east side of the Jordan as your homeland.\u2019
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Therefore, your wives, your little ones, and your livestock 
        may remain here, but all your valiant warriors must cross over with us armed. 
        They will take the lead and help their brothers "
      comments:
      - number: "1:13\u201314"
        content: "  Or \u201C[as] a place of rest.\u201D      The order here is significant:
          \u201Cyour wives, your little ones, and your livestock.\u201D When the
          two and a half tribes asked Moses to remain on the other side of the Jordan,
          they displayed a warped sense of their values by speaking of their possessions
          before their wives and children. See  .      Forty thousand warriors from
          these two and a half tribes crossed over to fight for their brothers (see 
          ). From  ,  ,  , we learn that about ninety thousand people of these tribes
          remained on the east side of the Jordan, including the women, children
          (those under the age of twenty), and the old men. Their new settlement
          was vulnerable, and they needed a fighting force to remain in case of attack.    "
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "\u201CRemember the words that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servant Moses commanded you: \u2018<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God
        is giving you this land on the east side of the Jordan as your homeland.\u2019
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Therefore, your wives, your little ones, and your livestock 
        may remain here, but all your valiant warriors must cross over with us armed. 
        They will take the lead and help their brothers "
      comments:
      - number: "1:13\u201314"
        content: "  Or \u201C[as] a place of rest.\u201D      The order here is significant:
          \u201Cyour wives, your little ones, and your livestock.\u201D When the
          two and a half tribes asked Moses to remain on the other side of the Jordan,
          they displayed a warped sense of their values by speaking of their possessions
          before their wives and children. See  .      Forty thousand warriors from
          these two and a half tribes crossed over to fight for their brothers (see 
          ). From  ,  ,  , we learn that about ninety thousand people of these tribes
          remained on the east side of the Jordan, including the women, children
          (those under the age of twenty), and the old men. Their new settlement
          was vulnerable, and they needed a fighting force to remain in case of attack.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "until they take possession of the land that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        your God is giving them as their homeland. [[COMMENT(0)]] Afterward, you
        will be free to return to your own land and possess the land that Moses,
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s servant, gave you here on the east side
        of the Jordan.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 1:15
        content: "  The unity of God\u2019s people is in focus in vv.  . Similarly,
          we must be willing to fight for our brother\u2019s victory as much as we
          fight for our own (see  ;  ;  ). This is one of the very points where the
          people would fail when we begin to read Judges. Everyone began to do what
          they wanted rather than to work together for the benefit of the whole community.     
          Joshua the prophet foresaw the complete victory of possessing the land
          of their enemies. In vv.    we learn that the land-takers were required
          to be united. Neither one individual nor one tribe could take the land;
          it required all God\u2019s people going in together and fighting as one.
          Battles are won as God\u2019s people unite. But unity alone isn\u2019t
          enough; we must be prepared for a battle over our complete inheritance.
          There must be no rest until everyone has received his or her inheritance.
          See  .    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "They answered Joshua: \u201CWe will do everything you have told us
        and will go wherever you send us. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'We always obeyed Moses, and we will always obey you. May <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        your God stand beside you as he stood with Moses. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "And anyone who questions your authority or disobeys whatever you
        command [[COMMENT(0)]] shall be put to death. So, Joshua, be strong and brave!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 1:18
        content: "  Literally \u201Cyour mouth.\u201D      Or \u201Cbe determined
          and confident!\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Joshua Sends Spies into Jericho'
      title: Joshua Sends Spies into Jericho
      number: 1
      content: "Then Joshua son of Nun secretly sent out two spies [[COMMENT(0)]]
        from their camp at Acacia.  He told them, \u201CGo and explore the land of
        Canaan, especially Jericho.\u201D <smallcaps>  </smallcaps> They went and
        arrived at Jericho and entered the house of Rahab the prostitute and lodged
        there.   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:1
        content: "  Joshua was one of the twelve spies sent out publicly by Moses
          (see  ). Some scholars believe that one of the spies could have been Salmon,
          who married Rahab, and whose son was Boaz. See  .      Archaeologists identify
          the location of Acacia with Tell el-Kefrein in modern Jordan. The Hebrew
          word for \u201CAcacia\u201D is  , which means \u201Cpiercing\u201D or \u201Cthorny.\u201D
          The acacia is a flowering hardwood tree. It was used to make the tabernacle
          furniture, including the ark of the covenant.      The Hebrew word for
          \u201CJericho\u201D is  , which means \u201Cmoon.\u201D Jericho was known
          as \u201CThe City of the Moon\u201D because of its occult worship of the
          moon god/goddess. The city, with its high double walls, was a capital of
          Canaanite worship. They considered their king to be a divine being. So
          when  gave the king over to be killed by Joshua and his men (see  ), they
          were, in effect, killing a \u201Cson of god.\u201D The earliest object
          of worship in the Canaanite religion was that of the male moon god Yerach.
          (See W. F. Albright,  , especially pp. 83 and 92; John Gray,  , p. 125.)     
          Although Josephus mentions that Rahab was an innkeeper (  5.1.2), the book
          of James clearly states she was a prostitute (see  ). It may be that she
          was both.    means \u201Covercome\u201D or \u201Covercomer.\u201D The Hebrew
          word    is also found in  . The Shulamite has \u201Crahab\u201D (overcome)
          the heart of the Beloved. The church fathers noted that Rahab possessed
          the spirit of prophecy, which the Jewish historian Josephus also mentions
          (see Josephus    5.1.13). She had a revelation that God was giving the
          land to Israel (see  ,  ). Rabbinical tradition states that Rahab was rewarded
          by having prophets and kings as her descendants.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "The king of Jericho was told: \u201CSome Israelites have come into
        the city tonight to spy out the entire land. They\u2019re in Rahab\u2019s
        house.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "So the king sent messengers to Rahab, who said to her: \u201CTurn
        over the men who entered your house. They\u2019re here to spy out our land.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "But Rahab had already hidden the two men.\u201CYes,\u201D she said.
        \u201CThe men came to me, but I had no idea where they were from. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "They left at sundown, just before the city gates were closed at night.
        Who knows where they went. Quick! Go after them, and maybe you can catch
        them!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:5
        content: '  Rahab protected the spies at the risk of her own life. She was
          a woman of faith. See  ;  .    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: '(Rahab had hidden the men on her rooftop under stalks of flax [[COMMENT(0)]]
        she had spread out to dry on the roof.) '
      comments:
      - number: 2:6
        content: '  Flax is a plant from whose stem a fiber was made that was woven
          into linen cloth. The valiant and virtuous woman (representing the radiant
          bride of Christ) also worked with flax. See footnote on  .    '
    - name: "7: Rahab\u2019s Pact with the Spies"
      title: "Rahab\u2019s Pact with the Spies"
      number: 7
      content: So the men of Jericho went out to search for the spies, and the city
        gates were shut behind them. They searched for them as far as where the path
        crosses the Jordan.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Before the spies had gone to sleep, Rahab went up to the rooftop '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "and said to them, \u201CI know that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has given you this land. Everyone is absolutely terrified, and we are all
        paralyzed with fear [[COMMENT(0)]] because of you. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:9
        content: "  Or \u201Ceveryone\u2019s heart melts with fear.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "We\u2019ve heard of the miracles that accompany you and how <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        dried up the waters of the Red Sea [[COMMENT(0)]] for you when you left Egypt.
        We\u2019ve heard how you utterly annihilated <smallcaps>.\u201D This term
        plays a significant role in the stories that follow concerning Jericho, Ai,
        and Achan.</smallcaps> the two Amorite kings, Sihon  and Og,   and their
        kingdoms who were on the other side of the Jordan.   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Sea of Reeds.\u201D      This is the Hebrew word 
          , meaning \u201Ctotally devoted, consumed, dedicated and given over to         
          means \u201Cto strike down.\u201D Sihon was an Amorite king who ruled over
          the city-state of Heshbon.    means \u201Cintelligence\u201D; this town
          represents the mind of man. In  , the ballad singers wrote songs about
          Heshbon and its king, which indicates how far the fame of Sihon has spread.
          The tribe of Gad eventually settled in the territory where Sihon once reigned.
          Jewish tradition states that Sihon and Og were both giants. The Jewish
          apocryphal book  , part of the Dead Sea Scrolls discovered at Qumran, states
          that Sihon and Og (Ogias) were brothers.        means \u201Clong-necked,\u201D
          \u201Cpride,\u201D or \u201Cintimidation.\u201D Og was the king of Bashan.
          Moses had fought and conquered his kingdom, which included over sixty fortified
          cities (see  ,  ). He was also a Rephaite giant or \u201Cterrible one.\u201D
          His iron bed was \u201Cnine cubits long and four cubits wide\u201D (thirteen
          and a half feet long and six feet wide). A man needing this size of bed
          was at least ten or eleven feet tall. See  . One of the cities the Israelites
          took from Og was Golan, which later became a Levitical city and a city
          of asylum (see  ).      See  .    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'As soon as we heard it, our hearts melted with fear, and we were
        left with no courage among us [[COMMENT(0)]] because of you. <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        your God, is the true God who rules in heaven above and on earth below. <smallcaps>.
        She is commended as a woman of faith. See</smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: 2:11
        content: "  Or \u201Ceveryone\u2019s spirit no longer rose up.\u201D     
          Rahab was a pagan Canaanite woman, yet she declared her faith in    ; 
          .    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Please, solemnly swear to me by the name of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        that you will show kindness to my family because I have shown kindness to
        you. Give me a sure sign '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "that you will spare the lives of my father and mother, my brothers
        and sisters, and all their families. Don\u2019t let us be killed!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "The men answered, \u201CIf you don\u2019t disclose our mission to
        anyone, we\u2019ll pledge our lives for yours. Then, when <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        gives us this land, we\u2019ll honor our promise and treat you kindly.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Rahab\u2019s house was built into the city wall, [[COMMENT(0)]] so
        she let them down from the window by a rope. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:15
        content: "  That is, a section of the city wall formed the outside wall of
          Rahab\u2019s house. Since this clause is not found in the Septuagint, some
          scholars believe it was a later scribal addition to the text.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "She told them, \u201CHead for the hill country and hide. The men
        chasing you won\u2019t find you there. Hide for three days until they have
        returned, then you\u2019ll be safe to go your way.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "But the men warned her, \u201CYou must do what we say, or we will
        not be bound to the oath you made us swear. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "When our invasion begins, bring all your family together in your
        house\u2014your father and mother, your brothers and sisters, and all their
        families. And tie this crimson rope [[COMMENT(0)]] in the same window through
        which you let us down. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:18
        content: "  This crimson rope can be seen in the light of the New Testament
          as an emblem of the blood of Jesus. Faith in Christ\u2019s blood brings
          us salvation. Rahab experienced a personal \u201CPassover\u201D because
          of the blood (crimson) applied to her house. Both Passover blood and the
          crimson rope were described in Hebrew as  , \u201Ca sign.\u201D See  ; 
          .    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Remember, if anyone ventures outside your house, his death will be
        his own fault, [[COMMENT(0)]] not ours! But if anyone inside your house is
        harmed, then we will be held responsible. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:19
        content: "  Literally \u201Chis blood will be on his own head.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "And if you disclose our mission, we will be released from the oath
        you made us swear.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Rahab replied in agreement, \u201CLet it be as you say.\u201D And
        she sent them away, and after they departed, she tied the crimson rope in
        her window."
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "The spies went straight to the hill country and hid there for three
        days, until the pursuers turned back. The king\u2019s men had scoured the
        countryside without finding them."
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Then the two men [[COMMENT(0)]] came down from the hills and crossed
        back over the Jordan to their camp. They reported to Joshua son of Nun all
        that had happened to them: '
      comments:
      - number: 2:23
        content: "  The two spies represent \u201Ctwo witnesses\u201D to establish
          and confirm their report. See  ;  .  "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has certainly handed over the
        entire land into our hands! All the people of the land melt in fear before
        us!\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Miracle-Crossing of the Jordan'
      title: The Miracle-Crossing of the Jordan
      number: 1
      content: 'Joshua was up bright and early the next morning. [[COMMENT(0)]] They
        broke camp, and Joshua led the Israelites from Acacia to the eastern bank
        of the Jordan.  There they set up camp and waited until they crossed over. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:1
        content: "  What an exciting day this was for Joshua and the people. They
          left their days of wandering in the wilderness behind. A new beginning
          was now before them. All but two men were under forty years old and had
          been born in the desert; now they would cross over into a fertile land.
          Anticipation was in the air! After three days of waiting before a flooding
          river, they were about to see a miracle! (For more examples of rising early,
          see  ;  ;  ;  ;  .)      This was a journey of about eight or nine miles,
          a day\u2019s walk with a crowd of a million people.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'After three days, [[COMMENT(0)]] the leaders of the people went throughout
        the camp '
      comments:
      - number: 3:2
        content: "  The reference to three days points us to the resurrection of
          Jesus Christ. The biblical significance of the number three refers to Jesus\u2019
          resurrection after three days.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "giving orders to the people, \u201CWatch for the priests of the tribe
        of Levi to lift the ark of the covenant of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]] your God. When it starts moving, follow it "
      comments:
      - number: 3:3
        content: "  The ark is the center of this story. It is mentioned or alluded
          to twenty-one (or 3 \xD7 7) times in chapters    and  . Twenty-one, in
          the language of biblical numbers, signifies a complete manifestation of
          God. The ark is a wonderful picture of our Lord Jesus Christ. The power
          of Christ within us enables us to pass over into our full inheritance.
          Jesus, our forerunner, leads us in. The ark was a constant reminder that
          God is powerful, holy, and to be obeyed. The ark also symbolizes God\u2019s
          mercy, for it had a mercy seat as a lid, or cover. Jesus is our Mercy Seat,
          or atoning sacrifice (see  ). Notice that it wasn\u2019t only the ark (Jesus)
          that went into the dry riverbed but also all of Israel. In the same manner,
          every believer today is co-crucified with Christ (see  ), and our \u201CAdam-nature\u201D
          was dismantled by the work of the cross (see  ).    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "so you\u2019ll know which way to go, since you\u2019ve never marched
        this way before. [[COMMENT(0)]] Follow about a half mile  behind the ark;
        don\u2019t go near it.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 3:4
        content: "  The Hebrew word    can mean \u201Cway\u201D or \u201Cmanner.\u201D
          They were to march in a new manner\u2014with their eyes on the ark (see 
          ). A new order for a new day. Before they crossed the Jordan, the ark had
          always been covered. Beginning when they crossed the Jordan and entered
          the promised land, the ark was in plain sight. In the Old Testament, Jesus
          was concealed; in the New Testament, Jesus is revealed. Without all the
          covering, the weight on the priests\u2019 shoulders would have been less.
          See  .      Or \u201Ctwo thousand cubits.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Joshua instructed the people, \u201CGet yourselves ready! Set yourselves
        apart [[COMMENT(0)]] for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>! Tomorrow, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        will perform for us great miracles!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 3:5
        content: "  Or \u201CSanctify yourselves,\u201D implying an inward attitude
          of purity and an outward washing and ritual purification. See  ;  ;  ; 
          . Both distance and attitude were important to God as the people followed
          the ark. We need both whole-hearted devotion and heart purity in our worship
          of God today. See  .      Some scholars are puzzled over the use of the
          plural word for miracles when it was only one miracle (parting the river).
          The plural implied the beginning of a new season of miracles and wonders
          as they crossed over.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Joshua told the priests, \u201CRaise up the ark of the covenant and
        step out ahead of the people.\u201D So they lifted the ark onto their shoulders
        and marched in front of the people."
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Joshua, \u201CThis very day
        I will begin to exalt you in the sight of all Israel [[COMMENT(0)]] so that
        they will realize that I am with you  in the same way I was with Moses. "
      comments:
      - number: 3:7
        content: "  The place of the miracle-crossing was the very place where John
          baptized Jesus (our Joshua).      God was with Joshua and God is with you.
          This would imply God\u2019s comforting presence, his power, and his delight
          to be at our side.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "You are to command the priests who carry the ark of the covenant
        with these words: \u2018Carry the ark to the edge of the Jordan and wade
        into the water.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 3:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cstand still in the Jordan.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Joshua told the Israelites, \u201CCome closer and listen to the words
        of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'This is how you will know for sure that the Living God is among you.
        As you advance into the land, he will drive out before you the Canaanites,
        Hittites, Hivites, Perizzites, Girgashites, Amorites, and Jebusites. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 3:10
        content: "  See  . The Canaanites and Amorites (see  ;  ) were the largest
          and most powerful tribes inhabiting the land. The Canaanites dwelt in the
          lowlands, and the Amorites were in the hill country (see  ). The Hittites
          lived in the northernmost parts of the land (see  ). The Hivites were associated
          with Shechem and Gibeon (see  ;  ;  ). The Jebusites had their stronghold
          at Jerusalem (see  ). The Perizzites are related to the Rephaites (\u201Cgiants,\u201D 
          ). The Girgashites were a branch of the Hivites and lived in the western
          region of the land. These seven tribes could also represent seven strongholds
          that must be conquered in the life of a believer: (1) The Hebrew word for
          \u201CCanaanites\u201D means \u201Cthose who traffic in materialism,\u201D
          \u201Cmerchants,\u201D or \u201Cpirates\u201D; they represent the love
          of money. (2) The Hebrew word for \u201CHittites\u201D means \u201Cthose
          broken in pieces,\u201D \u201Cterror,\u201D or \u201Cdread\u201D; they
          represent anger and violence. (3) The Hebrew word for \u201CHivites\u201D
          means \u201Clife born of effort\u201D or \u201Cbeastly life\u201D; they
          represent human effort and reliance upon self. (4) The Hebrew word for
          \u201CPerizzites\u201D means \u201Crustic,\u201D \u201Ccountry dwellers,\u201D
          or \u201Cbackwoods\u201D; they represent lack of vision and initiative.
          (5) The Hebrew word for \u201CGirgashites\u201D means \u201Cdense, condensed
          marshy ground\u201D; they represent ignorance, unwillingness to learn.
          (6) The Hebrew word for \u201CAmorites\u201D means \u201Cthose who live
          on high\u201D or \u201Csummit dwellers\u201D; they represent pride and
          arrogance. (7) The Hebrew word for \u201CJebusites\u201D means \u201Ctrampled
          down under foot\u201D; they represent fear and anxiety that cripple spiritual
          growth. Jesus, our heavenly Joshua, is more than enough to empower us to
          overcome these inner strongholds.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Look! The ark of the covenant of the Lord of all the earth will go
        before you and prepare a way for you through the Jordan. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: 3:11
        content: '  Joshua was expressing to Israel that if God can roll back the
          waters of a raging river, he can repel the attacking armies of Canaan.
          This miracle reminded these children of the Israelites who saw the waters
          of the Red Sea rolled back that they could experience the same wonder-working
          God moving on their behalf. Further, it signaled to the inhabitants of
          the land that the God of Israel was supreme over the gods of the waters
          (gods which were untamable and uncontrollable to the Canaanites). As  had
          overthrown the gods of Egypt, so he would overcome the gods of Canaan.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: Now select twelve men from among the people, one man from each tribe.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 3:12
        content: '  On the discourse level, this verse is somewhat out of place.
          The twelve men are not Levitical priests but representatives of the tribes.
          Further details of their duties are given in the next chapter (see  ).    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CThe moment the feet of the priests carrying the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the Lord of all the earth, touch the water of the Jordan, a great miracle
        will happen! The water flowing downstream toward you will stop and pile up
        as if behind a dam.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14-15: '
      title: 
      number: 14-15
      content: "Now it was time for the early harvest, [[COMMENT(0)]] and the river
        was overflowing at flood stage. When the people broke camp to cross the Jordan,
        the priests went in front of them carrying the ark of the covenant on their
        shoulders. The very moment the priests with the ark dipped their feet in
        the river\u2019s edge, "
      comments:
      - number: "3:14\u201315"
        content: "  The tributaries of the Jordan, swollen with the spring snowmelt
          from Mount Hermon, flooded the river valley. The width of the flooding
          river could have been up to a mile at the time of the miracle-crossing.
          (See  .) By comparing  ;    with  , we learn that Israel\u2019s miracle-crossing
          took place in the spring when both barley and flax were harvested, four
          days before Passover.    "
    - name: '14-15: '
      title: 
      number: 14-15
      content: "Now it was time for the early harvest, [[COMMENT(0)]] and the river
        was overflowing at flood stage. When the people broke camp to cross the Jordan,
        the priests went in front of them carrying the ark of the covenant on their
        shoulders. The very moment the priests with the ark dipped their feet in
        the river\u2019s edge, "
      comments:
      - number: "3:14\u201315"
        content: "  The tributaries of the Jordan, swollen with the spring snowmelt
          from Mount Hermon, flooded the river valley. The width of the flooding
          river could have been up to a mile at the time of the miracle-crossing.
          (See  .) By comparing  ;    with  , we learn that Israel\u2019s miracle-crossing
          took place in the spring when both barley and flax were harvested, four
          days before Passover.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'the water coming downstream toward them stopped flowing and piled
        up in a solid wall as far upstream as Adam, a place near Zarethan. [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> completely cut off the flow of the river so
        that it drained downstream toward the Desert Sea (the Dead Sea).  So the
        people crossed over opposite Jericho. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:16
        content: "  Adam is seventeen miles north of the place of the miracle-crossing,
          and Zarethan is another twenty miles north. The waters were held back and
          formed a lake that would have extended for almost forty miles. Notice the
          name \u201CAdam.\u201D The Jordan represents the death of Jesus on the
          cross and the price he paid to save us. The word for \u201CJordan\u201D
          is a compound word joining the words for \u201Cto descend\u201D and \u201Cjudging\u201D
          (judgment; see    and footnote). Jesus, pictured as the ark, descended
          into judgment for our sins and rolled the river of guilt, shame, and judgment
          all the way back to Adam! The root word for    is a verb that means \u201Cpiercing\u201D
          or \u201Cbleeding of the veins.\u201D Judgment was abated to Adam by the
          one who was \u201Cpierced\u201D for our rebellious deeds. It was both the
          ark and the people who crossed over. Our old Adam-life was buried figuratively
          at the crossing, and we were \u201Cresurrected\u201D with him to possess
          our inheritance as a people set free (see  ).      Or \u201Cthe Sea of
          Arabah (Salt Sea).\u201D A very wide path opened for the people to cross
          over on dry ground. The \u201Cwaters of death and judgment\u201D stopped
          flowing when Jesus our Savior was crucified. Now, when we believe, the
          fountain of living waters opens within us.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Now the priests stood firmly on dry ground in the riverbed with the
        ark on their shoulders. [[COMMENT(0)]] The entire nation passed by the ark
        as they completed their miracle-crossing on dry ground. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:17
        content: "  We are also \u201Cpriests\u201D of God (;  ) who \u201Cstand
          firm\u201D in the finished work (\u201Cdry ground\u201D) of the cross and
          resurrection of Christ and who carry the ark of his glory in our hearts
          (see  ).      The miracle-crossing of the Jordan bore many similarities
          to the parting of the Red Sea. (1) Both involved water. (2) Both were witnessed
          by the entire nation of Israel. (3) Both involved an act of a servant of
          God\u2014Moses stretched out his rod over the water, and Joshua commanded
          the priests and the people. (4) Both removed a barrier to the forward advance
          of God\u2019s people. (5) Both miracles vindicated God\u2019s leader (see 
          ;  ). (6) Both required the obedience of God\u2019s people (see  ;  ).
          (7) Both miracles enabled Israel to cross over on dry ground (see  ). (8)
          Both miracles were performed while God\u2019s people stood still (see 
          ; footnote on  ). (9) Both the waters of the Red Sea and of the Jordan
          were restored to their places. (10) Both miracles became a hinge of history,
          marking a new beginning. (11) Both miracles revealed God\u2019s tremendous
          power to defeat his enemies. (12) Both miracles resulted in songs of praise
          (see  ;  ;  ).  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Two Stone Memorials Established'
      title: Two Stone Memorials Established
      number: 1
      content: 'When the entire nation had finished their miracle-crossing of the
        Jordan, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Joshua, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CChoose twelve men, [[COMMENT(0)]] one from each of the twelve
        tribes of Israel. "
      comments:
      - number: 4:2
        content: '  Jesus, our heavenly Joshua, likewise chose twelve men to be his
          disciples.    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Instruct each of them to take a stone from the riverbed, twelve stones
        from the very place where the priests stand with the ark. Have them carry
        the stones over to the place where you camp tonight.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'So Joshua summoned the twelve men he had selected from the Israelites,
        one per tribe. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Joshua instructed them, \u201CWalk out to the middle of the riverbed
        to the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God. Each of you choose
        a stone and lift it up onto your shoulder\u2014one stone for each tribe. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "The stones will always be a sign to you. Someday, when your children
        ask you, \u2018Why are these stones so important?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "tell them, \u2018The Jordan stopped flowing in front of the ark of
        the covenant of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2014the floodwaters were completely
        cut off.\u2019 These stones will serve as a memorial for Israel forever.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: The Israelites did as Joshua commanded them. They took twelve stones
        according to the number of the tribes of Israel, from the middle of the riverbed,
        and carried them to the camp and put them there.
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Joshua set up the memorial stones that they had taken from the exact
        spot [[COMMENT(0)]] where the priests stood bearing the ark in the riverbed.
        They remain there to this day. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:9
        content: "  Or \u201CJoshua set up the stones in the exact spot,\u201D which
          would imply there may have been a second set of memorial stones (one set
          on land and another on the riverbed).      The Talmud states that these
          stones were still at that very spot even a generation after the destruction
          of the Second Temple, and that three rabbis stood on top of them (Talmud,   
          34a).    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "While the priests remained standing in the middle of the Jordan with
        the ark on their shoulders, the people hurried across. All the instructions
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had given to Joshua were carried out [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014just
        as Moses had told Joshua.   "
      comments:
      - number: 4:10
        content: '  For the priests to stand still for many hours with the heavy
          ark on their shoulders was a test of their strength, patience, and courage.
          We also are priests in the kingdom of God, and we are called upon to possess
          those same qualities.      See  .    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: And when Israel had finished crossing, the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        and the priests crossed as the people looked on.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The Reubenites, the Gadites, and half the tribe of Manasseh went
        across, armed and ready for battle, in front of the Israelites, as Moses
        had commanded them. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 4:12
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: In all, about forty thousand men were equipped for battle. And they
        all marched before <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> to wage war on the plains
        of Jericho.
      comments: []
    - name: '14: The Jordan Returns to Flood Stage'
      title: The Jordan Returns to Flood Stage
      number: 14
      content: On that day, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> exalted Joshua before all
        the people. As they had stood in awe of Moses, so they stood in awe of Joshua
        for the rest of his life.
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Joshua, [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 4:15
        content: '  Joshua heard the voice of God in real time.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CCommand the priests carrying the ark of the covenant [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to come up from the Jordan.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 4:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe ark of testimony [instruction].\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'So Joshua did as he was commanded, '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: and the priests carrying the ark of the covenant of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        came up from the riverbed. And the moment their feet touched the western
        bank of the Jordan, the floodwaters surged back in place where they were
        before and returned to flood stage.
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'The people experienced the miracle-crossing of the Jordan on the
        tenth day of the first month of the Jewish calendar. [[COMMENT(0)]] They
        established their base camp at Gilgal,  east of Jericho,   '
      comments:
      - number: 4:19
        content: "  The \u201Cfirst month\u201D is the month of Abib, which began
          with the first new moon occurring after March 11 on the Gregorian calendar,
          so the crossing occurred between March 21 and April 18. It was on this
          same day forty years earlier that Israel set apart the Passover Lamb in
          Egypt (see  ,  ). (See Keil,  , 51.)        means \u201Ccircle\u201D or
          \u201Crolling away.\u201D      Or \u201Con the east border of Jericho,\u201D
          which was about halfway between the Jordan and Jericho.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'where Joshua set up a memorial with the twelve stones taken from
        the Jordan. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "He told the Israelites, \u201CIn time to come, when children ask
        their fathers, \u2018Why are these stones so important?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "tell them, \u2018Here is the place where the Israelites crossed the
        Jordan on dry ground!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'For your God, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, dried up the waters
        of the Jordan before your eyes until you crossed over, [[COMMENT(0)]] just
        as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God did for us years ago; he dried
        up the Red Sea while we crossed over! '
      comments:
      - number: 4:23
        content: "  Elijah had a repeat of this miracle-crossing (see  ). Those who
          walk in the \u201Cspirit of Elijah\u201D today can likewise expect miracles
          in their ministry. Elisha, who had a double portion of the spirit of Elijah,
          also performed the miracle-crossing (see  ; cf.  ).    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "He has done these miracles so that all the earth will be in awe [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of the mighty power  of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> and that you might
        always obey   <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 4:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cknow firsthand\u201D from the Hebrew word  .      Or
          \u201Chand.\u201D      Or \u201Cfear,\u201D which has a varied universe
          of meanings in Hebrew. The two miracles\u2014the parting of the Red Sea
          and the miracle-crossing of the Jordan\u2014carry a message for the entire
          world to learn. As believers in our heavenly Joshua, our Lord Jesus, we
          can learn from the symbolism of these miracles. The Red Sea parting shows
          us deep lessons of our salvation from sin, and so does the Jordan crossing.
          We were co-buried with Christ in baptism into his death (Jordan), and now
          we are co-raised with him on the \u201Cdry ground\u201D of resurrection
          territory (see  ;  ).  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: God\u2019s People at Gilgal"
      title: "God\u2019s People at Gilgal"
      number: 1
      content: All the Amorite kings west of the Jordan and all the Canaanite kings
        along the coast of the Mediterranean Sea became terrified of the Israelites.
        For when they heard how <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> miraculously dried
        up the Jordan so that the Israelites could cross over, all their courage
        melted away.
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "At that time, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> commanded Joshua, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> \u201CMake knives of flint and circumcise  the men of Israel
        again.\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 5:2
        content: "  and Joshua were friends. How wonderful to know that God will
          converse with his servants.      Circumcision, the cutting off of the foreskin
          from the penis, was the sign of the covenant that God made with Abraham
          (see  ). The reason for doing this is given in  . The male children born
          while Israel was wandering in the wilderness for forty years had not been
          circumcised. This would leave Israel vulnerable for a number of days as
          the men healed.      Or \u201Cthe second time.\u201D All male Israelites
          had been circumcised before their exodus from Egypt (see  ), so this would
          be the nation\u2019s second time.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: So Joshua made stone knives and circumcised all the men at a place
        they named Circumcision Hill. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 5:3
        content: "  Or \u201CGibeath Haaraloth.\u201D    means \u201CHill of Foreskins.\u201D
          There could have been more than a half million men who were circumcised
          at that time. The Hebrew word for \u201Ccircumcision\u201D is  , which
          means \u201Cto cut short,\u201D \u201Cto blunt,\u201D \u201Cto destroy,\u201D
          or \u201Cto cut in pieces.\u201D The principle of circumcision is that
          the flesh (human nature apart from divine influence) must be cut off and
          removed if God\u2019s people are to enter into the fullness of their spiritual
          inheritance (see  ;  ). Circumcision was performed on the eighth day after
          birth (see  ). Eight is the number of a new beginning. The circumcision
          of the heart (see  ;  ;  ;  ) frees us to hear from God, to live in the
          Spirit of God (see  ), and to enter into the fullness of God (see  ).    "
    - name: '4-6: '
      title: 
      number: 4-6
      content: "Joshua had to circumcise all the men and boys\u2014all the fighting
        men. Although they had been circumcised before leaving Egypt, the male children
        born during the forty years they spent in the wilderness had not been circumcised.
        Also, by the end of that forty years, all the fighting men who had come out
        of Egypt had died because they had not listened to the voice of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
        So <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had made an oath that they would not see
        the land he had promised to give their ancestors, a fertile land. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4-6: '
      title: 
      number: 4-6
      content: "Joshua had to circumcise all the men and boys\u2014all the fighting
        men. Although they had been circumcised before leaving Egypt, the male children
        born during the forty years they spent in the wilderness had not been circumcised.
        Also, by the end of that forty years, all the fighting men who had come out
        of Egypt had died because they had not listened to the voice of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
        So <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had made an oath that they would not see
        the land he had promised to give their ancestors, a fertile land. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4-6: '
      title: 
      number: 4-6
      content: "Joshua had to circumcise all the men and boys\u2014all the fighting
        men. Although they had been circumcised before leaving Egypt, the male children
        born during the forty years they spent in the wilderness had not been circumcised.
        Also, by the end of that forty years, all the fighting men who had come out
        of Egypt had died because they had not listened to the voice of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
        So <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had made an oath that they would not see
        the land he had promised to give their ancestors, a fertile land. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: So he raised up their sons in their place, and Joshua circumcised
        them because they had not been circumcised on the way.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'After the circumcision was completed, the whole nation waited in
        the camp until their wounds had healed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Joshua, \u201CToday, I
        have rolled away your disgrace from being slaves in Egypt.\u201D For that
        reason, the place is named Gilgal [[COMMENT(0)]] to this day."
      comments:
      - number: 5:9
        content: "    means \u201Ccircle\u201D or \u201Croll away.\u201D It became
          their headquarters during the early days of their conquest of Canaan.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'While encamped at Gilgal, not far from Jericho, [[COMMENT(0)]] the
        Israelites celebrated the Feast of Passover  in the evening of the fourteenth
        day of the month of Abib.   '
      comments:
      - number: 5:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cin the plains of Jericho.\u201D      The Feast of Passover
          commemorated their deliverance from slavery in Egypt. See  .      Abib
          was the first month of the Jewish ecclesiastical calendar and was later
          changed to Nisan after the Babylonian captivity. It is roughly April in
          the Gregorian calendar.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "The very next day, they ate for the first time food grown in Canaan\u2014roasted
        grain and flatbread made without yeast. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: The Commander of the Armies of Heaven'
      title: The Commander of the Armies of Heaven
      number: 12
      content: On that day, when they ate the produce of the land, the manna [[COMMENT(0)]]
        stopped falling from heaven. The Israelites never ate manna again, but that
        year they enjoyed the fruit of the land of Canaan.
      comments:
      - number: 5:12
        content: "    means \u201Cwhat is it?\u201D See  ,  . For forty years, God
          supernaturally fed his people in the wilderness (see  ). Manna is also
          called \u201Cangels\u2019 food\u201D ().    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "When Joshua was near Jericho, he looked up and saw standing in front
        of him a man holding a drawn sword. [[COMMENT(0)]] Joshua approached him
        and said, \u201CAre you on our side or on our enemies\u2019?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 5:13
        content: '  There is nothing in the text to indicate that this was a vision.
          Joshua physically saw this tangible man before him.    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CNeither,\u201D he replied. \u201CI have not come to take sides
        but to take charge. [[COMMENT(0)]] I am the Commander of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        armies.\u201D   At once, Joshua threw himself facedown to the ground and
        worshiped,  and he said to him, \u201CI will do whatever you command, my
        Lord.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 5:14
        content: "  This encounter was not a matter of Joshua gaining the allegiance
          of the Lord but of the Lord gaining the allegiance of Joshua.      No doubt,
          the imposing walls of Jericho that stood before Israel intimidated Joshua.
          Suddenly the Commander came to take over the leadership of his armies.
          Also, these armies were not only earthly but also the greater armies of
          the angelic host that stood ready to follow their heavenly Commander into
          battle. See  . He was about to give Joshua a supernatural and illogical
          strategy for taking the city of Jericho.      Joshua worshiped this \u201CCommander,\u201D
          showing that he was neither an angel nor a human messenger but Jesus. This
          was a Christophany (a pre-incarnate appearing of Christ). Furthermore,
          the Commander called the ground Joshua was upon \u201Choly\u201D because
          of the presence of the Holy One. Compare  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "The Commander of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s armies said
        to Joshua, \u201CRemove your sandals, for you are standing on holy ground!\u201D
        And Joshua obeyed. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s armies, knowing that
        he will lead us forward in \u201Cendless triumph\u201D (</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 5:15
        content: "  See  . This chapter teaches us many principles to prepare us
          to enter our own spiritual \u201Cpromised land\u201D to claim our endless
          spiritual blessings (see  ). First, we cross over into a new day, burying
          our old identity in Jordan\u2019s flood. Second, we submit our hearts to
          Jesus (Joshua), cutting off flesh, experiencing the circumcision of the
          heart. Third, we enjoy a Passover Feast, receiving full deliverance from
          sin and victory over our enemies (see  ). Fourth, we get a new diet for
          conquerors (see  ). Manna (the life of Christ while he was on earth) has
          ceased, and the new roasted grain has become our feast. Jesus passed through
          the fires of God\u2019s judgment for our sins and has now become the grain
          of wheat who fell into the ground (see  ). Now he is raised with many grains
          of wheat (our co-resurrection with Christ, see  ). We eat the unleavened
          bread of single-hearted devotion and purity in the love feast we enjoy
          in Christ (see  ). Fifth, we encounter the Commander of  ). These principles
          prepare us to enter into our spiritual promised land and into a new dimension
          of spiritual warfare (see  ).  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Capture of Jericho'
      title: The Capture of Jericho
      number: 1
      content: Now the gates of Jericho were bolted and barred because of the Israelites;
        no one could get in or out.
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> commanded Joshua, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s
        armies, identified here as</smallcaps><smallcaps>.</smallcaps> \u201CSee,
        I have given Jericho, its king and mighty warriors into your hands.   "
      comments:
      - number: 6:2
        content: "  If we see v.    as parenthetical, then Joshua was still in the
          presence of the Commander of          Faith will see \u201Cwhat is still
          unseen\u201D (). God gave Joshua a promise upon which to rest his faith.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'March around the city with all your men of war once a day for six
        days. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Have seven priests carry shofars in front of the ark. On the seventh
        day, march around the city seven times, with the priests blowing the shofars. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "When you hear the blare of the shofars, have all the people shout
        with a mighty shout of joy! [[COMMENT(0)]] Then the walls  of the city will
        collapse before your eyes, and your whole army must charge straight in!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 6:5
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Cshout\u201D is    and can be either
          a war cry or a shout of joy.      The walled city of Jericho could represent
          the stronghold of the natural mind and every high thought that exalts itself
          against the knowledge of the true God (see  ). Walls represent our inner
          \u201Cwalls\u201D and arguments we erect against learning something new.
          The mind of man is opposed to the ways of God (see  ;  ). The door to truth
          is not the intellect but rather the spirit yielded to God. Daniel saw the
          writing on the wall, and knew the walls of Babylon would fall (see  , 
          ). Ezekiel dug through the \u201Cwall\u201D to uncover the abominations
          that were hidden (). The prophet Joel saw an army that would run upon and
          climb up the \u201Cwalls\u201D (). David was a champion who leapt over
          the \u201Cwall\u201D (; see  ). And similarly, Joshua was a prophetic leader
          who shouted so that the \u201Cwalls\u201D could topple ().      The perimeter
          of Jericho was about four miles. God designed this unorthodox military
          strategy to demonstrate his power (see  ), to discourage all forms of self-reliance,
          and to bring all the glory to himself (see  ). The thick, impenetrable
          walls (see  ;  ) were nothing against the power of God!    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So Joshua son of Nun summoned the priests and instructed them: \u201CTake
        up the ark of the covenant, and have seven priests carry seven shofars in
        front of the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "And to the people he said, \u201CForward! March around the city and
        set an advance guard of armed men to march ahead of the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "At Joshua\u2019s order, the seven priests carrying seven shofars
        advanced before <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. The ark of the covenant of
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> followed them as they made long blasts on their
        shofars. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'The advance guard marched in front of the priests who were blowing
        the shofars, the rear guard marched behind the ark, and the shofars blared
        the whole time! '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Now Joshua had commanded the rest of the people, \u201CDo not shout!
        Remain silent! Don\u2019t make a sound until the moment I command you to
        shout. Then lift up a shout with all your might!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: So the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> circled the city once,
        then they all came back to the camp in Gilgal and spent the night.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Joshua rose bright and early the next morning, and the priests took
        up the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'The armed men and the seven priests carrying the seven shofars marched
        in front of the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> blowing their shofars
        continually, and the rear guard followed the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        while the trumpets kept sounding. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: On the second day, they circled the city once and again returned to
        the camp. They repeated this pattern for six days.
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'On the seventh day, everyone rose at daybreak, and they marched around
        the city in the same manner seven times. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "After their seventh time around, when the priests were about to blow
        the shofars, Joshua commanded the people: \u201CShout a shout of joy! <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has given you the city! "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Jericho and everything in it are to be a devoted offering to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] But spare Rahab the prostitute and everyone in her house because
        she hid our spies. '
      comments:
      - number: 6:17
        content: "  The Hebrew term for \u201Cdevoted offering\u201D is    and implies
          things or persons who were entirely and irrevocably consecrated to God,
          often by total destruction. See  .    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'You must not take for yourselves [[COMMENT(0)]] anything that is
        dedicated to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> or you will bring trouble and
        destruction to the entire Israelite camp!   '
      comments:
      - number: 6:18
        content: "  Or \u201Ckeep away from.\u201D      See  .    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Everything made of silver, gold, bronze, and iron is sacred and devoted
        to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>; place all of it in <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        treasury!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The people were ready to shout with a great shout when they heard
        the shofars. As soon as they heard the blast of the shofars, they raised
        a massive shout of jubilee like a thunderclap, and all at once the thick
        walls of Jericho collapsed! Everyone rushed straight ahead [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and captured the city. '
      comments:
      - number: 6:20
        content: "  Or \u201Ceveryone ascended.\u201D By comparing v.    with  ,
          we see that both events have the Lord himself (see  ), a shout, a trumpet
          blast, and the people ascending. There are a number of \u201Csevens\u201D
          in this chapter: seven priests, seven shofars, seven days circling the
          city, seven times the city was to be encompassed on the seventh day. Seven
          represents completion, fullness, and perfection.    "
    - name: '21: Rahab and Her Family Are Spared'
      title: Rahab and Her Family Are Spared
      number: 21
      content: "They utterly destroyed all that was in Jericho, men and women, young
        and old, livestock and donkeys\u2014everything was destroyed with the sword.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 6:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cby the mouth of the sword.\u201D See  .    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Joshua told the two spies who had entered Jericho, \u201CGo to the
        prostitute\u2019s house and rescue her and everyone in her house, just as
        you promised her.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: So the two spies brought out Rahab, her father, mother, brothers and
        sisters, and all who belonged to her, and gave them refuge outside the camp
        of Israel.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then they burned Jericho to the ground and all that was within it.
        Only the silver and gold, brass, and iron were placed into the treasury of
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s house. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Yet Joshua spared Rahab the prostitute, her father\u2019s family,
        and all that belonged to her. She lives among the Israelites to this day
        [[COMMENT(0)]] because she hid the two men Joshua sent to spy out Jericho."
      comments:
      - number: 6:25
        content: '  This shows that the book of Joshua was written not long after
          the events of the book.    '
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Afterward, Joshua pronounced this solemn oath:\u201CMay <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        curse anyonewho attempts to rebuild this city, Jericho!He will pay for laying
        its foundationwith the life of his oldest son,and for setting up its gates
        with his youngest son!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 6:26
        content: '  This curse was fulfilled 550 years later in the time of Ahab
          by Hiel the Bethelite (see  ). In contrast, our heavenly Father laid the
          foundation of the church (see  ) with the death of his Firstborn (see 
          ). The younger son is the overcomer, the many sons brought to glory, we
          who will also lay down our lives to rebuild the gates of Zion.  '
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s presence was with Joshua, and
        he became famous throughout the land."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Achan\u2019s Sin"
      title: "Achan\u2019s Sin"
      number: 1
      content: "But the Israelites violated the commandment regarding the wealth
        of Jericho that was to be set apart for the Lord. Achan [[COMMENT(0)]] son
        of Carmi,  grandson of Zimri,  of the clan of Zerah,  from the tribe of Judah,
        stole some of the devoted things for himself. This ignited <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anger against Israel."
      comments:
      - number: 7:1
        content: "    means \u201Cone who brings trouble.\u201D Just as there was
          a snake in the garden (see  ), Judas among the followers of Christ (see 
          ), and Ananias and Sapphira in the church (see  ), so there was \u201Cone
          who brings trouble\u201D in the midst of Israel. See  .        means \u201Cmy
          vineyard.\u201D      Or \u201CZabdi\u201D or \u201CZabri\u201D (see   
          LXX).      Through Zerah, Achan was the descendant of Judah\u2019s sexual
          sin. See  .    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Joshua sent spies from Jericho to Ai (a small city near Beth Aven,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] southeast of Bethel), with orders to spy out the land. So
        the spies left for Ai.   '
      comments:
      - number: 7:2
        content: "    means \u201Chouse of wickedness.\u201D      Ai was about fifteen
          miles north of Jericho. Tradition identifies the site known as et-Tell
          as biblical Ai.    means \u201Cheap of ruins.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "When they returned to Joshua, they reported to him, \u201CThere is
        no need to trouble the whole army to conquer Ai. The people are so few that
        two or three thousand men could attack it and take the city.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 7:3
        content: '  Nothing in our spiritual life is so small that we can war against
          it in our own strength without God.    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'So Joshua sent three thousand troops to attack the city, but they
        were routed by the men of Ai. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "The men of Ai chased them from the city gates, down the hill as far
        as the quarries, [[COMMENT(0)]] cutting them down as they fled. They killed
        thirty-six of Joshua\u2019s men, and when Israel heard of their defeat, their
        hearts melted away with fear! "
      comments:
      - number: 7:5
        content: "  Or \u201CShebarim.\u201D    means \u201Cquarries\u201D or \u201Cravines.\u201D     
          Or \u201Cmelted away and turned to water.\u201D It is interesting to note
          that after a great spiritual victory, we are all susceptible to a painful
          defeat. Only as we walk in divine strength and become aware of our weakness
          can we experience victory (see  ). This event warns us all of the sins
          of pride and presumption. All our fountains are in Christ (see  ).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Joshua and the elders of Israel tore their clothes and threw dust
        over their heads to show their sorrow. [[COMMENT(0)]] They threw themselves
        facedown to the ground in front of the ark of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        until the evening sacrifice.   '
      comments:
      - number: 7:6
        content: "  Tearing one\u2019s clothes and throwing dust on one\u2019s head
          were ancient acts of mourning. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  .      This was the time
          of the evening sacrifice of a lamb.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Joshua cried out, \u201CO&nbsp;Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        why did you lead these people across the Jordan? To be defeated? To be killed
        by the Amorites? If only we had been content to stay on the other side of
        the Jordan! "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'O&nbsp;Lord, what can I say now that Israel has retreated from its
        enemies? '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "When the Canaanites and everyone else in the land hear about our
        defeat, they will gang up on us and wipe us off the face of the earth. And
        what then will you do about your great name?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:9
        content: "  That is, \u201CWhat will you do to protect your great reputation?\u201D
          Joshua pleaded with God to consider that his reputation was at stake over
          the success and protection of his people.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to Joshua: \u201CStand up! Why
        are you groveling before me? "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Israel has sinned! [[COMMENT(0)]] They have broken the covenant which
        I had commanded them to keep. They have taken forbidden plunder. They have
        stolen from me, taken what is mine, hidden it among their belongings, and
        lied about it. '
      comments:
      - number: 7:11
        content: "  The defeat at Ai was not just because they did not pray and trust
          God; it was because there was sin in the camp of Israel and they had lost
          God\u2019s favor. Although it was one individual, Achan, who sinned, God
          viewed them as a unit. We are one body in Christ, and the victory of one
          is the victory of all, and the sin of one is the sin of all. See  . For
          the righteousness of one (Rahab), the whole of her family was saved. For
          the sin of Achan, the whole of his family was condemned. Thus it is imperative
          that we belong firmly to the family of God in Christ Jesus, our eldest
          brother and representative head.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Cursed things are among you! That is why Israel is powerless, has
        retreated from their enemies, and is in danger of annihilation. If you do
        not get rid of these cursed things from among you, I will not go with you
        any longer. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Get up and purify the people in preparation for tomorrow. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Tell them, \u2018This is what <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of Israel
        says: \u201CO&nbsp;Israel, you have in your midst what must be devoted entirely
        to me! You cannot stand against your enemies until you remove the devoted
        things from your midst!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 7:13
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Tomorrow morning, you shall present yourselves by tribes. <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        will indicate [[COMMENT(0)]] which tribe must come forward by clans. <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        will indicate which clan must come forward by families. And <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        will indicate which family must come forward one by one. '
      comments:
      - number: 7:14
        content: "  Or literally \u201Ccatch by lot.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Then finally, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> will expose the man caught
        with the devoted things, which must be destroyed by fire. Everything that
        man owns [[COMMENT(0)]] you must likewise destroy by fire, for he has violated
        the covenant of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> and committed an outrageous
        act in Israel!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 7:15
        content: "  Or \u201CAll who belong to him.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Joshua was up at the crack of dawn and had Israel come forward by
        tribes, and <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> indicated [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> the tribe of Judah. '
      comments:
      - number: 7:16
        content: "  Although Joshua does not record the manner in which  picked out
          Judah, we know that it was through a supernatural act of communication,
          possibly the Urim and Thummim. (  means \u201Clights\u201D and    means
          \u201Cperfections.\u201D) See  ;  ;  . During the entire process, Achan
          had ample time to step forward and repent.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Joshua then had the clans of Judah come forward, and <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        picked out the clan of Zerah. Joshua then had the clan of Zerah come forward
        and <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> indicated the family of Zimri. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Joshua then had Zimri\u2019s family come forward one by one, and
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> picked out Achan, the son of Carmi, son of
        Zimri, son of Zerah, of the tribe of Judah."
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Then Joshua said to Achan, \u201CMy son, give glory to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, [[COMMENT(0)]] and confess.  Tell me the truth and do
        not hide anything from him. What have you done?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 7:19
        content: "  \u201CGive glory to God!\u201D was a Hebraism by which Joshua
          demanded the truth from Achan. (See footnote on  .)      Or \u201Cgive
          him praise.\u201D To admit our sin before God in heartfelt confession is
          equated with giving praise to God.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CIt\u2019s true,\u201D Achan said. \u201CI\u2019ve sinned against
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of Israel. This is what I did: "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "I saw among the plunder an exquisite robe from Babylon, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        two hundred pieces of silver, and a fifty-shekel bar of gold.  I wanted them
        badly, so I took them <smallcaps>  </smallcaps> and buried them in my tent
        with the silver underneath.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 7:21
        content: "  Or \u201CShinar.\u201D See  ;  ;  . Babylonia was recognized
          for its splendid, costly robes of many colors. It is possible that this
          robe had idolatrous figures embroidered on it. It may have been the royal
          robe of the king of Jericho. See  .      This was equivalent to about five
          pounds of silver and one pound (or twenty ounces) of gold.      Achan followed
          the same order in his sin as Adam and Eve: he saw, he wanted them, and
          he took them. See  ;  ;  . This is in the heart of sinful creation in rebellion
          against the goodness of God\u2019s generosity and holiness. Similarly,
          Achan sought to hide himself (he did not come forward but required  to
          expose him). Similarly, the family of Achan was condemned for his sin in
          the same fashion that the descendants of Adam are condemned for his sin.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Joshua sent messengers who ran to the tent, and there it was! They
        found it buried in the middle of the tent with the silver underneath. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'They took the stolen objects from the tent, [[COMMENT(0)]] brought
        them to Joshua and all the Israelites, and displayed them in the presence
        of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.   '
      comments:
      - number: 7:23
        content: "  Buried in our dust, in our \u201Ctent-life\u201D (see  ), we
          often try to hide our sins. It is always better to live without shame and
          without hidden things. Joshua\u2019s (Jesus\u2019) messengers will uncover
          the hidden things and bring them to the light (see  ) so that victory may
          be restored. Our sins affect not only ourselves but those around us as
          well.      Most likely, the stolen objects were laid in the tabernacle
          before the ark of glory.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then Joshua, and all Israel with him, took Achan son of Zerah along
        with the silver, the robe, the bar of gold, and all that belonged to him\u2014his
        sons, daughters, donkeys, oxen, sheep, tent\u2014everything. Joshua led them
        all to the Valley of Trouble [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 7:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Valley of Achor.\u201D    (related to Achan) means
          \u201Ctrouble\u201D or \u201Cdisaster.\u201D But judgment is not the end
          of the story. For the believer today, God\u2019s loving heart will open
          a door of hope for us even in the Valley of Trouble (see  ; see  ). Jesus
          turns the Valley of Trouble into a door of hope. He took our judgment that
          we might rise up in resurrection\u2019s hope. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "and said, \u201CWhy have you brought all this trouble on us? <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        will bring trouble on you today!\u201DThen all the people stoned Achan and
        his family to death. They burned up the bodies and all Achan\u2019s possessions. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "They raised over him a huge mound of stones that remains to this
        day. That is why the place was called the Valley of Trouble ever since.Afterward,
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s anger subsided against Israel. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:26
        content: "  Leadership lessons we can learn from this chapter include: (1)
          There are times the advice of others can lead us astray (see v.  ). (2)
          It is dangerous for leaders to be presumptuous, to be self-confident, and
          to ignore sin (see v.  ). (3) We can never take anything that has been
          devoted to God (see v.  ). (4) Our message to the people must bring them
          into purity (see v.  ). And (5) keeping ourselves pure will restore favor
          and blessing to God\u2019s people (see v.  ).  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ai Conquered'
      title: Ai Conquered
      number: 1
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Joshua, \u201CDo not yield
        to fear nor shrink back because of Israel\u2019s failure. Now, get up, take
        all your soldiers with you, and march against Ai. See, I have handed over
        to you [[COMMENT(0)]] the city, the king, his people, and his land. "
      comments:
      - number: 8:1
        content: "  Or \u201CI have delivered into your hands.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Do to Ai what you did to Jericho and its king, except this time,
        you may take the plunder, including livestock. Set an ambush behind the city.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Joshua and his entire army set out to attack Ai. He chose thirty
        thousand valiant warriors and sent them ahead by night '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "with these instructions: \u201CNow pay attention. Set an ambush behind
        Ai, but don\u2019t hide very far away. Stay alert and ready for battle! "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "I\u2019ll lead the rest of the army and make a direct assault on
        the city, and when they come out to fight us, we\u2019ll flee from them as
        we did the first time. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "When this happens, they\u2019ll say to themselves, \u2018Look! They\u2019re
        running away from us, just like last time!\u2019 And they\u2019ll keep chasing
        us until we\u2019ve lured them away from the city. While we\u2019re running
        away from them, "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'jump up from your hiding place, race into Ai, and seize it. <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        your God, will deliver the city into your hands! '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "When you\u2019ve captured the city, set it on fire. Now that you
        have your orders, go and do as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has commanded!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: Joshua then sent them off, and they proceeded to take up a concealed
        position west of Ai, between Ai and Bethel, while Joshua spent the night
        with the rest of the troops.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'So early the next morning, Joshua mustered his troops. He and the
        leaders of Israel went in front of the army and led them toward Ai. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The entire fighting force with Joshua advanced until they were near
        the city and encamped north of Ai, [[COMMENT(0)]] with a valley between them
        and the city. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:11
        content: '  Joshua encamped in plain sight of the enemy.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'He placed a smaller force of about five thousand men west of the
        city to set an ambush between Bethel and Ai. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 8:12
        content: '  Some Jewish scholars (Rashi, David Kimchi) suggest that Joshua
          set a double ambush, one closer to the city than the other. One consisted
          of five thousand and the larger ambush, thirty thousand.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'The main fighting force north of the city prepared for battle, while
        the rear guard [[COMMENT(0)]] held a concealed position west of the city.
        Joshua spent the night in the valley. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:13
        content: "  Or \u201Chis heel.\u201D      The Septuagint omits v.    entirely.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'At dawn, when the king of Ai saw the Israelites, he and his army
        rushed out to fight. They ran to attack Israel at a predetermined place en
        route to the Arabah, not knowing that an ambush had been set against them
        behind the city. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Joshua and all the main fighting force fled toward the wilderness
        as though they were being overcome. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Joshua\u2019s tactic drew all of Ai\u2019s reinforcements out of
        the city, and they set off in hot pursuit of Joshua and his men. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: Not a man remained in Ai or in Bethel [[COMMENT(0)]] who did not go
        out in pursuit of Israel, leaving their city undefended.
      comments:
      - number: 8:17
        content: '  The reference to Bethel is omitted in the Septuagint.    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to Joshua and said, \u201CNow,
        take the spear in your hand and point it toward Ai, for I will hand the city
        over to you!\u201D So Joshua pointed his spear toward the city, "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: and when Joshua gave this signal, all the men waiting in ambush behind
        the city jumped up from their position and poured into Ai. They quickly captured
        it and set it on fire.
      comments: []
    - name: '20-21: '
      title: 
      number: 20-21
      content: 'When the men of Ai looked back, they saw the smoke of their city
        rising to the sky. Joshua and his men also saw the smoke and knew that the
        other Israelite soldiers had captured the city and had set it on fire. The
        army of Ai had no place to escape, so Joshua and his men turned on them and
        began killing them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20-21: '
      title: 
      number: 20-21
      content: 'When the men of Ai looked back, they saw the smoke of their city
        rising to the sky. Joshua and his men also saw the smoke and knew that the
        other Israelite soldiers had captured the city and had set it on fire. The
        army of Ai had no place to escape, so Joshua and his men turned on them and
        began killing them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'The men who had taken the city came out and joined the battle, so
        the Israelites had them surrounded. Israel cut them down, leaving neither
        survivors nor fugitives. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: But they captured the king of Ai alive and brought him to Joshua.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Joshua\u2019s men killed all the inhabitants of Ai in the fields
        and in the wilderness where they had chased them. They all fell by the sword.
        Then the Israelites turned to attack Ai and killed those who were still there.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 8:24
        content: "  God did a miracle for Israel with Jericho\u2019s walls crumbling,
          but with the battle of Ai, it was God\u2019s brilliant strategy carried
          out by Joshua\u2019s men that won the victory. Every battle in our lives
          requires that we seek God\u2019s face and obey his instructions so that
          we will taste the joys of victory. Obedience to God\u2019s plan is the
          key. Though God assured Israel of victory, they still had to discharge
          their responsibility.    "
    - name: '25-26: '
      title: 
      number: 25-26
      content: "Joshua kept his spear pointed at Ai until the destruction was complete.
        Ai\u2019s entire population, twelve thousand men and women, fell that day. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25-26: '
      title: 
      number: 25-26
      content: "Joshua kept his spear pointed at Ai until the destruction was complete.
        Ai\u2019s entire population, twelve thousand men and women, fell that day. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: However, the Israelites took the livestock and the goods captured
        in the city as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had instructed Joshua.
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Then Joshua burned Ai to the ground and reduced it to a mound of
        ruins for all time. It remains desolate to this day. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: Renewal of the Covenant at Mount Ebal'
      title: Renewal of the Covenant at Mount Ebal
      number: 29
      content: And he hanged the king of Ai on a tree until sunset. Then at sunset,
        Joshua had the corpse taken down and left it lying in front of where the
        city gates once stood. They raised a large pile of stones over his corpse,
        where it remains to this day.
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Afterward, Joshua built near Mount Ebal a stone altar [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of Israel. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:30
        content: "  This altar was built at Shechem, about twenty miles from Ai,
          between Mount Ebal and Mount Gerizim.    means \u201Cstripped of all covering,\u201D
          \u201Cbare,\u201D \u201Cnaked,\u201D or \u201Cbarren.\u201D The law etched
          upon stones exposes sin, leaves us guilty, and produces death (see  ).    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "He made it according to the teaching in the law of Moses, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servant. Moses had commanded them to build an altar using stones that had
        not been cut with iron tools. [[COMMENT(0)]] On it they offered to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        burnt sacrifices and fellowship offerings.   "
      comments:
      - number: 8:31
        content: "  See  . Building the altar without the tools of people teaches
          us that God alone made the ultimate altar, the cross of Jesus. Salvation
          is not through the hands of humankind but by the mercy of God (see  ).
          The altar was to be on Mount Ebal, the place where the curses were read.
          God has provided an altar of salvation even when sin\u2019s curse defeats
          us. Mercy\u2019s altar stands on Ebal even when we feel stripped, bare,
          naked, and barren.      Or \u201Cpeace offerings,\u201D \u201Cofferings
          of well-being,\u201D or \u201Ccommunion sacrifices.\u201D The fellowship
          offerings were given in gratitude to God. Only the fat was burned (see 
          ), and the rest was consumed by the people (see  ).    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: And with the Israelites looking on, Joshua inscribed on stones the
        law which Moses had written.
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "All Israel, including their elders, officials, and judges, stood
        on either side of the ark. Both native-born citizens and immigrants alike
        faced the ark of the covenant of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> and the Levitical
        priests who carried it. In front of half of them stood Mount Gerizim, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> and in front of the other half stood Mount Ebal, as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servant Moses commanded at first to bless the people of Israel.   "
      comments:
      - number: 8:33
        content: "    means \u201Ccut up\u201D or \u201Cshorn place.\u201D Jesus
          took our curse and was \u201Cshorn\u201D and \u201Ccut up\u201D for our
          sins (see  ). Israel renewed their covenant with  in the valley between
          Mount Ebal (  means \u201Cstripped of all covering,\u201D a picture of
          the law) and Mount Gerizim (  means \u201Ccut up,\u201D a picture of the
          cross of Jesus Christ). The new covenant, the Spirit of Life, is now written
          upon our hearts. See  ;  ;  ;  .      See  .    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'Afterward, Joshua read aloud all the words of the law, the blessings
        and the curses, [[COMMENT(0)]] exactly as it was written in the scroll of
        the law. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:34
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: Joshua read aloud every word that Moses had commanded, and all the
        assembly of Israel heard it, including the women, the children, and the foreigners
        who accompanied them. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 8:35
        content: '  See  .  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Gibeonites Deceive Joshua'
      title: The Gibeonites Deceive Joshua
      number: 1
      content: "Now when all the kings west of the Jordan heard about these things\u2014those
        in the hill country, [[COMMENT(0)]] in the western foothills, and along the
        entire coast of the Great Sea as far as Lebanon (the kings of the Hittites,
        Amorites, Canaanites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites)\u2014"
      comments:
      - number: 9:1
        content: '  This was a hilly area on the west of the Jordan called the Shephelah.
          The kings of the highlands could represent those today who occupy the high
          ground of pride and fleshly confidence. They look down from their elevated
          position on anyone who is unlike them.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'they came together to make war against Joshua and Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'When the inhabitants of Gibeon [[COMMENT(0)]] learned how Joshua
        had destroyed Jericho and Ai, '
      comments:
      - number: 9:3
        content: "  The kings mentioned in this passage could represent those today
          who oppose God\u2019s ways:    means \u201Chill city,\u201D representing
          human pride,    means \u201Chuman effort,\u201D and    means \u201Cheap
          of ruins.\u201D Gibeon was the capital of the Hivites, a large city about
          seven miles from Ai and nearly twenty miles from Israel\u2019s camp at
          Gilgal. It has been identified with modern al-Jib, a Palestinian village
          about six miles northwest of Jerusalem.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'they resorted to a ruse: They sent a delegation disguised [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        as messengers from a distant land. They loaded their donkeys with worn-out
        sacks and old, patched wineskins. '
      comments:
      - number: 9:4
        content: "  Or possibly \u201CThey collected provisions.\u201D The meaning
          of the Hebrew is uncertain.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'They wore old, patched sandals on their feet and old, tattered clothes,
        and took along dry, moldy bread. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "When they arrived at Israel\u2019s camp at Gilgal, they said to Joshua
        and the Israelites: \u201CWe\u2019ve come from a far country to propose that
        you make a treaty with us.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The men of Israel asked the Hivites, \u201CPerhaps you live nearby.
        Why should we make a treaty with you?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 9:7
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CWe are willing to be your servants,\u201D they answered Joshua.Joshua
        questioned them further, \u201CWho are you and where are you from?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "The Gibeonites replied: \u201CYour servants come from a very distant
        land because we\u2019ve heard of the fame of your God, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
        We\u2019ve heard of his wonders and all that he did in Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "We\u2019ve also heard of all he did to help you defeat the two Amorite
        kings on the other side of the Jordan\u2014King Sihon of Heshbon and King
        Og of Bashan, who lived in Ashtaroth. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 9:10
        content: '  They did not mention the more recent miraculous conquests of
          Jericho and Ai.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Therefore, our leaders and all the inhabitants of our land sent us
        to find you with these instructions: \u2018Get food ready for your long trip,
        and go to the Israelites and say to them, \u201CMake a treaty with us. We\u2019re
        willing to be your servants.\u201D&nbsp;\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Look at our bread! It was still warm when we left home with it. See
        how dry and moldy it\u2019s become! "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "These wineskins were new when we filled them. See how they\u2019ve
        dried up and burst! And look, our clothes and sandals are worn out from our
        long journey.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 9:13
        content: "  The Gibeonites with old wineskins (religious systems), old clothing
          (old nature), old worn-out shoes (old methods), and moldy bread, represent
          counterfeit traditions and deceptions of religion. Their bread was moldy,
          not fit for consumption. The boast of their \u201Clong journey\u201D parallels
          the ecclesiastical history of many church traditions today that have confidence
          in their long history more than the authority of Scripture. We can make
          no alliance with the old as we move forward to possess our inheritance.
          A new victory requires that we eat the fresh bread of heaven with a renewed
          mind that hears what God is saying today to his people.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "The leaders of Israel ratified a peace treaty with the Gibeonites
        by sharing a meal together, [[COMMENT(0)]] but they failed to consult with
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. <smallcaps>.\u201D Some Jewish scholars believe
        that meant they did not ask the Lord to show them what to do through the
        Urim and Thummim. If we lack wisdom and ask God, he will give us his heart
        (see</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: 9:14
        content: "  Literally \u201CThe men took some of their provisions.\u201D
          This was not simply eating the moldy bread but also a sharing of a fellowship
          meal to ratify the peace treaty.      Or \u201Cthey did not ask the mouth
          of    ).    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: Joshua agreed to let them live. He made a peace treaty with them,
        and the leaders of the assembly sealed it with an oath.
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'But three days after the treaty had been made, the Israelites learned
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  that they had been deceived. In fact, the Gibeonites were
        from the local area and lived nearby. '
      comments:
      - number: 9:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cheard.\u201D It is possible that Israel supernaturally
          heard that the Gibeonites were lying, perhaps through a dream or from a
          prophet among them who heard from God.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'So the Israelites set out at once, and on the third day, they came
        to their cities: Gibeon, Chephirah, [[COMMENT(0)]] Beeroth,  and Kiriath
        Jearim.   '
      comments:
      - number: 9:17
        content: "    means \u201Clioness.\u201D It has been identified with the
          modern Khirbet el-Kefireh, about ten miles west of Jerusalem.        means
          \u201Cwells.\u201D        means \u201Ccity of dense thickets\u201D (representing
          the mind of man). Kiriath Jearim is also called Kiriath Baal (see  ). The
          four cities in this verse were clustered close together: Beeroth was about
          five miles northeast of Gibeon; Chephirah was about five miles southwest
          of Gibeon, and Kiriath Jearim was a bit farther away in the same direction.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'But the Israelites did not attack them because the leaders of the
        assembly had sworn an oath to them in the name of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel.This caused Israel to grumble against their leaders, '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "but the leaders told the assembly of Israel, \u201CWe cannot touch
        them, for we swore an oath to them in the name of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20-21: '
      title: 
      number: 20-21
      content: "We must let them live for fear that God\u2019s anger will come upon
        us because of the oath we swore to them.\u201D So they became woodcutters
        and water carriers for the community of Israel, as their leaders had decreed."
      comments: []
    - name: '20-21: '
      title: 
      number: 20-21
      content: "We must let them live for fear that God\u2019s anger will come upon
        us because of the oath we swore to them.\u201D So they became woodcutters
        and water carriers for the community of Israel, as their leaders had decreed."
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Joshua summoned the Gibeonites and asked them, \u201CWhy did you
        deceive us? You told us that you lived very far from us, but we now know
        for a fact that you live right here near us. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Therefore, we will spare your lives, but you will live under a curse,
        and you will be condemned to perpetual servitude. You will serve the house
        of my God by cutting wood and carrying water for us.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 9:23
        content: "  See  . Cutting wood and carrying water were the tasks of women
          in the culture of that day. The implication is that the Gibeonites would
          have had to disband their army and depend on Israel for their defense.
          Furthermore, cutting wood and carrying water would be very important tasks
          for tabernacle worship when Israel set up their base in Shiloh (see  ).
          Though they were considered servants and uncircumcised gentiles, they would
          be close in proximity to the worship of  in the tabernacle and serve the
          needs of the sacrificial system. Historically, the Gibeonites retained
          their treaty rights with Israel for more than four hundred years, until
          the close of David\u2019s reign. One violation of their treaty occurred
          under Saul\u2019s reign, and it brought Israel three years of famine as
          God\u2019s judgment. See  . Principles of any covenant are very important
          to God.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "They answered Joshua, \u201CWe lied, sir, because we greatly feared
        for our lives. We know for certain all about Moses and how he served <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        your God. We know for certain that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> will honor
        his promise to Moses and give you all these lands as your own. And we know
        for certain that he commanded you to wipe out all the inhabitants living
        here and thus take possession of this land. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Now we are at your mercy, so do with us what you consider right and
        proper.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'So Joshua had mercy and saved them [[COMMENT(0)]] from being killed
        by the Israelites. '
      comments:
      - number: 9:26
        content: "  Israel\u2019s sons once made a treaty with the people of Shechem
          but broke it and killed the people (see  ). Here Joshua made a peace treaty
          and kept his oath. Like Joshua, leaders must always keep their promises
          and show mercy to others. At times, our past sins do affect our lives.
          The consequences of our sins may later surface so that we can learn from
          the past and break off its influence by the power of the Holy Spirit.    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: That day, he made them woodcutters and water carriers to serve the
        community of Israel for the altar of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> at his
        divinely chosen place. [[COMMENT(0)]] And that is what they do to this day.
      comments:
      - number: 9:27
        content: '  See  ,  ,  ;  ;  ;  .  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1-2: When the Sun Stood Still'
      title: When the Sun Stood Still
      number: 1-2
      content: 'Adoni-zedek, [[COMMENT(0)]] the king of Jerusalem,  was struck with
        fear when he  heard how Joshua had totally destroyed the kings and cities
        of Ai and Jericho and that the people of Gibeon had made a peace treaty with
        Israel and were living alongside them. The city of Gibeon was larger than
        Ai, as large as any of the cities that were ruled by a king, and all its
        men were known as great warriors. '
      comments:
      - number: "10:1\u20132"
        content: "  The high-sounding names of the five kings mentioned in this chapter
          all speak of human pride, self-righteousness, and the natural life with
          its five senses.    means \u201Clord of righteousness.\u201D There is only
          one Lord of Righteousness, and it wasn\u2019t he.      This is the first
          mention of Jerusalem in the Bible.    means \u201Cfoundation of peace\u201D
          or \u201Ccity of peace.\u201D The city was originally known as the stronghold
          of Jebus or Jerus. Later, in about 1010 BC, David captured the stronghold
          of the Jebusites and established Jerusalem as the capital of his united
          kingdom. See  .      Or \u201Cthey.\u201D This was not only the people
          of Jerusalem but the four other kings as well (see v.  ). The kings of
          that land were struck with fear because of God\u2019s miracles that accompanied
          Israel. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '1-2: When the Sun Stood Still'
      title: When the Sun Stood Still
      number: 1-2
      content: 'Adoni-zedek, [[COMMENT(0)]] the king of Jerusalem,  was struck with
        fear when he  heard how Joshua had totally destroyed the kings and cities
        of Ai and Jericho and that the people of Gibeon had made a peace treaty with
        Israel and were living alongside them. The city of Gibeon was larger than
        Ai, as large as any of the cities that were ruled by a king, and all its
        men were known as great warriors. '
      comments:
      - number: "10:1\u20132"
        content: "  The high-sounding names of the five kings mentioned in this chapter
          all speak of human pride, self-righteousness, and the natural life with
          its five senses.    means \u201Clord of righteousness.\u201D There is only
          one Lord of Righteousness, and it wasn\u2019t he.      This is the first
          mention of Jerusalem in the Bible.    means \u201Cfoundation of peace\u201D
          or \u201Ccity of peace.\u201D The city was originally known as the stronghold
          of Jebus or Jerus. Later, in about 1010 BC, David captured the stronghold
          of the Jebusites and established Jerusalem as the capital of his united
          kingdom. See  .      Or \u201Cthey.\u201D This was not only the people
          of Jerusalem but the four other kings as well (see v.  ). The kings of
          that land were struck with fear because of God\u2019s miracles that accompanied
          Israel. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So King Adoni-zedek of Jerusalem sent messages to King Hoham [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of Hebron, King Piram of Jarmuth,  King Japhia of Lachish,  and King Debir
        of Eglon:   '
      comments:
      - number: 10:3
        content: "    means \u201Cdriven [forced]\u201D or \u201Che crushed.\u201D
          He ruled as king of Hebron, twenty miles south of Jerusalem.    means \u201Calliance.\u201D       
          means \u201Cwild donkey\u201D or \u201Cfierce.\u201D Piram ruled as king
          of Jarmuth (modern Khirbet el-Yarmuk), which is eighteen miles southwest
          of Jerusalem.    means \u201Chigh place.\u201D These high places could
          also include \u201Cevery arrogant attitude that is raised up in defiance
          of the true knowledge of God\u201D ().        means \u201Cone who enlightens\u201D
          or \u201Celevated.\u201D Japhia ruled as king of Lachish, fifteen miles
          west of Hebron.    means \u201Cinvincible.\u201D Archeologists believe
          that Tell el-Hesy is ancient Lachish.        means \u201Cspeaker\u201D
          or \u201Coracle.\u201D Debir was the king of Eglon, ten miles west of Hebron.   
          means \u201Cyoung bull.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CThe people of Gibeon have made peace with Joshua and the Israelites.
        Come and help me attack them.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "The five Amorite kings joined forces\u2014the kings of Jerusalem,
        Hebron, Jarmuth, Lachish, and Eglon. [[COMMENT(0)]] Their combined armies
        surrounded Gibeon and attacked it."
      comments:
      - number: 10:5
        content: "  The combined forces of these five city-states would have been
          quite intimidating, to say the least. However, it was in fact God\u2019s
          plan to bring them together and to defeat them in one epic battle. This
          chapter describes the miraculous way in which their coalition was defeated
          and how the God of Israel gave victory to Joshua.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "The Gibeonites sent out a call for help to Joshua [[COMMENT(0)]]
        at the camp in Gilgal: \u201CDon\u2019t abandon us, for we are your servants!
        Come quickly and save us! Help us, for the Amorite kings of the hill country
        have surrounded us!\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 10:6
        content: "  Even though the men of Gibeon were \u201Cgreat warriors,\u201D
          they didn\u2019t trust in their own strength but called for help to Joshua
          (Jesus). See  ;  .      The five kings occupied the high ground, standing
          above everyone else. Their elevated position is a picture of pride in a
          perceived higher status. Many believers today look down on others who are
          not like themselves. See  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: So Joshua and all his fighting men, all the mighty warriors of Israel,
        left Gilgal to aid the Gibeonites.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to Joshua: [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> \u201CDo not fear the Amorite kings and their armies, for I
        have decreed your victory over them; not one will withstand you!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 10:8
        content: "  Once again,  spoke to his servant, Joshua. We need leaders today
          who hear the voice of our Champion-God and help others to hear God\u2019s
          voice for themselves. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Joshua and his fighting force marched all night long from Gilgal
        to Gibeon  [[COMMENT(0)]] and took them all by surprise! '
      comments:
      - number: 10:9
        content: '  This march, over rough, uphill country, took about nine hours
          to complete.    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Joshua inflicted a crushing defeat on them at Gibeon, for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        threw the Amorites into a panic at the sudden sight of Israel\u2019s army!
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  empowered Joshua  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps>  and his army
        to chase them in the direction of the Beth Horon ascent,   and they slaughtered
        the kings\u2019 armies all the way to Azekah    and the city of Makkedah.   "
      comments:
      - number: 10:10
        content: "  The Hebrew text indicates that  is still the subject in vv. 
          .  empowered the army, after an all-night march, to fight victoriously
          over the coalition of the Amorites.  also empowered them to run for many
          miles when Israel\u2019s fighting force turned south from Beth Horon all
          the way to Azekah and Makkedah. This was a supernatural event not accomplished
          by the might of Israel\u2019s army alone. They were given supernatural
          strength by faith (see  ).      Beth Horon was two towns. Upper Beth Horon
          was about five miles northwest of Gibeon. There was a mountain pass that
          descended to lower Beth Horon.      The exact site of Azekah is unknown,
          but it is believed to be in or near the Valley of Elah. David famously
          fought Goliath in the Valley of Elah, about fifteen miles southwest of
          Bethlehem, probably modern Wadi es-Sant.      The exact location of Makkedah
          is unknown, but it is believed to be el-Mughar, twenty-five miles from
          Gibeon.    means \u201Cshepherd\u2019s field.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "As the Amorites raced down the hill to Beth Horon, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        hurled large hailstones on them from the sky! [[COMMENT(0)]] The hail continued
        to fall all the way to Azekah; in fact, more men died from <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        hailstones than by the swords of the Israelites."
      comments:
      - number: 10:11
        content: "  God supernaturally directed the hailstones to hit the Amorites,
          but not the Israelites (see  ). There have been reports in human history
          of record hailstones weighing over 120 pounds. The largest hailstone in
          recent history fell in South Dakota, US, and was nearly the size of a volleyball.
          Hail is a biblical symbol of God\u2019s truth and justice that destroy
          the refuge (web) of lies. See  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> gave the men of Israel victory over
        the Amorites that day, the day when Joshua stood before the people and prayed
        to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>:\u201CSun, stand still [[COMMENT(0)]] over
        Gibeon!Moon, stay where you are over the valley of Aijalon!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 10:12
        content: "  Or \u201CSun, wait silently.\u201D        means \u201Cfield of
          deer\u201D or \u201Ca strong place.\u201D The fiery passion of the Lord
          (see  ;  ) consumed Joshua as he spoke to the sun and moon so he could
          finish the fight. What faith we see in his decree! Imagine if that zeal
          came upon you.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And so the sun stood still in the middle of the sky and was in no
        hurry to set until one day became two. And the moon halted while the nation
        triumphed [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> over its enemies\u2014as
        it is also recorded in the Scroll of the Upright One.   "
      comments:
      - number: 10:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cexacted vengeance.\u201D This chapter contains perhaps
          the most amazing miracle recorded in Israel\u2019s history. By the decree
          of a mortal, the entire cosmos paused as  himself fought for his people!
          God will go to any length to see you win your battles as you live in faith
          and obedience to him. God is the engineer of the universe and holds its
          controls in his hands. He can accelerate or slow down the created order
          he set in place. See  ;  ;  .      Or \u201CJashar.\u201D See  . Jashar
          is from the Hebrew word  , which means \u201Cupright,\u201D \u201Ccorrect,\u201D
          or \u201Cpleasing.\u201D The scroll\u2019s name can also be translated
          \u201Cthe Song of Heroes\u201D or \u201Cthe True Record.\u201D The    was
          a book likely containing war songs, prayers, and exploits of Israel. The
          Jewish sage Rashi believed \u201CJashar\u201D was a symbolic name for the
          Torah. Others believe it is the same as the book of the wars of the Lord
          (see  ). There has been no manuscript found containing the  . There are
          other books by that name, but they are not the same as the one mentioned
          here.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "It was the day <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> himself fought for Israel!
        There has never been a day like it before or since\u2014a day when <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        obeyed the voice of a man!"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: Joshua Captures the Five Amorite Kings'
      title: Joshua Captures the Five Amorite Kings
      number: 15
      content: After their victory, [[COMMENT(0)]] Joshua and his fighting men returned
        to their camp at Gilgal.
      comments:
      - number: 10:15
        content: "  Scholars debate whether or not this is a scribal error, mistakenly
          copied from v.    and placed here. Regardless, the narrative doesn\u2019t
          end yet, for the battle continued as they captured the kings of the opposing
          forces and executed them.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Meanwhile, the five Amorite kings fled and hid in a cave at Makkedah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'When Joshua was told that the five kings had been found hiding in
        a cave at Makkedah, '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Joshua ordered his men, \u201CSeal up the mouth of the cave with
        large stones and post guards in front of it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "But don\u2019t stop! Pursue your enemies! Cut off their retreat and
        don\u2019t let them reach their cities, for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        your God has given them into your hand!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "So Joshua and the Israelites nearly killed them all\u2014almost to
        a man\u2014although a few escaped into the fortified cities. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: The whole army returned safely to Joshua at the camp in Makkedah.
        No one dared speak against the Israelites. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 10:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cno one so much as snarled [or \u2018sharpened their
          tongue\u2019] at the Israelites.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Then Joshua ordered, \u201COpen up the cave and bring the five kings
        out to me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "So Joshua\u2019s men removed the five kings from the cave, the king
        of Jerusalem, the king of Hebron, the king of Jarmuth, the king of Lachish,
        and the king of Eglon, and brought them before Joshua."
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Joshua summoned all of Israel and ordered his army officers, \u201CPlace
        your feet on the necks of these kings.\u201D So they placed their feet upon
        their necks! "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Then Joshua said to his officers, \u201CNever be afraid of your enemies
        or let them discourage you. Be strong and filled with courage! <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        is going to do to all your enemies what he\u2019s done to these kings!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Then Joshua had the kings executed and hanged on five trees, and
        he left them there until evening. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: The Capture of the Cities of the South'
      title: The Capture of the Cities of the South
      number: 27
      content: At sunset, Joshua ordered them taken down from the trees and thrown
        into the cave where they had been hiding. He had large stones rolled over
        the mouth of the cave, and they remain there to this day. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 10:27
        content: "  Joshua had imprisoned the five Amorite kings and set men as guardians
          over the cave until he had defeated their armies. Then his men opened the
          cave and brought out the kings, and he invited the men of war to put their
          feet on the necks of these enemies as a symbol of total victory. Joshua
          executed the five kings, hanging them on five trees. Without revelation,
          our five natural senses rule and limit us. A mind set on the five senses
          (metaphorically represented by the five kings) is like a cave and tomb
          of darkness. In the same way Joshua shut the mouth of the cave with stones,
          Jesus (our Joshua) set guardians over the church (see  ;  ). Jesus pounds
          our enemies to a pulp under our feet (see  ;  ), a total victory. In the
          same way Joshua executed the five kings, Jesus has silenced all the voices
          accusing and condemning us (see  ) and has set us free from the curse of
          legalistic self-effort (see  ). He crucified our old identities, and they
          are dead and buried. We no longer live submitted to sin\u2019s power because
          Jesus gives us new life and new identities, empowered by his faith (see 
          ;  ).    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: That day, Joshua captured Makkedah, annihilated the inhabitants, and
        put its king to the sword, leaving no survivors. And he did to its king what
        had been done to the king of Jericho.
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'From Makkedah, Joshua and his army marched southwest to the city
        of Libnah [[COMMENT(0)]] and attacked it. '
      comments:
      - number: 10:29
        content: "    means \u201Cpavement\u201D or \u201Cwhiteness.\u201D Libnah
          lies about seven miles southwest of Makkedah.    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: By the power of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the city and its king
        were handed over to the Israelites. They annihilated all the inhabitants
        with the sword, leaving no survivors. And they did to its king what they
        had done to the king of Jericho.
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'From Libnah, Joshua and his army marched south to the city of Lachish
        and attacked it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'By the power of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the city was handed
        over to Joshua on the second day of the battle. They annihilated all the
        inhabitants of the city, just as they had done to Libnah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: Meanwhile, Horam, [[COMMENT(0)]] king of Gezer,  had marched out to
        help Lachish, but Joshua defeated him and his army, leaving no survivors.
      comments:
      - number: 10:33
        content: "    means \u201Cexalted.\u201D        means \u201Csteep\u201D;
          it is about twenty-two miles north of Lachish.    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'Then Joshua and all the Israelite army marched on from Lachish to
        attack the city of Eglon. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 10:34
        content: "    means \u201Cbull-like\u201D; it is about ten miles west of
          Lachish.    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: By the power of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, they captured the
        city in one day and destroyed its inhabitants, just as they had done to Lachish.
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'Then Joshua and all the Israelite army marched from Eglon and attacked
        Hebron. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 10:36
        content: "    means \u201Calliance\u201D; it is in the highlands about twenty-two
          miles from Eglon.    "
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: By the power of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, they captured the
        city, the king, and nearby villages, and totally wiped out all the inhabitants,
        leaving no survivors, just as they had done to Eglon.
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'Lastly, Joshua and all the Israelite army turned around and attacked
        Debir. '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: By the power of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, they captured the
        city, the king, and nearby villages, and totally wiped out all the inhabitants,
        leaving no survivors. They did to Debir and its king as they had done to
        Libnah and its king and to Hebron.
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  empowered Joshua to conquer the whole
        region, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> including the hill country,
        the southern desert,  the western foothills, and the mountain slopes. He
        conquered all the kings of the land and left no survivors. Everything that
        breathed was slaughtered\u2014as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of
        Israel, had commanded.   "
      comments:
      - number: 10:40
        content: "  These seven victories (including the defeat of Horam\u2019s army)
          established the Israelites in the land and made the name of  famous.     
          Or \u201CNegeb.\u201D      The utter destruction of the cities and people
          of the land God gave to Israel reflects our need to identify and destroy
          absolutely everything in our lives that hinders God\u2019s grace from subduing
          and conquering our hearts. No doubt it was not a pleasant task for Israel,
          nor is it a pleasant task for a believer today. Nevertheless, we must set
          apart the \u201Cpromised land\u201D of our hearts for God alone, with neither
          compromise nor hidden sin. It is our responsibility to seek out and destroy
          anything in our lives that might corrupt a single-hearted devotion and
          pure love for a holy God (see  ;  ). With God\u2019s divine grace, nothing
          is impossible (see  ;  ). We will share the likeness of Jesus and become
          the radiant, look-alike partners to the Son of God (see  ).  "
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "Joshua\u2019s conquest stretched from Kadesh Barnea to Gaza, and
        from Goshen to Gibeon. "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'Joshua conquered all their kings and their lands in a single campaign,
        for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, fought for his people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: Finally, Joshua and all the Israelite army returned to their base
        camp in Gilgal.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Joshua\u2019s Northern Conquest"
      title: "Joshua\u2019s Northern Conquest"
      number: 1
      content: "When the news of Israel\u2019s southern victories reached King Jabin
        [[COMMENT(0)]] of Hazor,  he organized a massive coalition to fight against
        Israel. He sent messages to:King Jobab of Merom, the king of Shimron, the
        king of Achshaph, "
      comments:
      - number: 11:1
        content: "    means \u201Cdiscerner\u201D or \u201Cwise one.\u201D       
          means \u201Cfortified\u201D or \u201Ccastle.\u201D It was a major city-state
          that lay about nine miles north of Lake Galilee.      Or \u201CMadon.\u201D   
          means \u201Cstrife.\u201D Some scholars, because of historical and archaeological
          evidence, prefer to read \u201CMerom\u201D (v.  ) here and in  . Merom
          was three miles west of Lake Galilee.        means \u201Cextreme vigilance.\u201D
          It was a city-state of the Lower Galilee region and the Jezreel Valley.
          It is identified today as Tell Samunia or Tell Shimron.        means \u201Cincantation\u201D
          or \u201Csorcery.\u201D The exact location of Achshaph is unknown, but
          it is believed to be about thirty miles from Hazor.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'the kings of the northern hill country, [[COMMENT(0)]]the kings of
        the Jordan Valley south of Lake Galilee, the kings of the foothills,the western
        kings in the heights of Dor, '
      comments:
      - number: 11:2
        content: "  The northern hill country would be the modern district of Galilee.     
          Or \u201CArabah south of Chinneroth [Galilee].\u201D In biblical times,
          Arabah referred both to the Jordan Valley between Lake Galilee and the
          Dead Sea, and also to an area south of Judah.      Or \u201Cthe foothills
          of the Carmel range.\u201D This was the region west of Lake Galilee toward
          the Mediterranean coastal plains south of Mount Carmel.    means \u201Clofty
          place\u201D; it was the chief city.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: the eastern and western Canaanite kings,the Amorite kings,the Hittite
        kings,the Perizzite kings,the Jebusite kings in the highlands,and the Hivite
        kings who lived near Mount Hermon in the land of Mizpah. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 11:3
        content: "    means \u201Cwatchtower.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'They came out in full force with a multitude of horses and chariots.
        Their vast armies were as numerous as the grains of sand on the seashore.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>!</smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:4
        content: '  According to Josephus, the armies of these ten kingdoms were
          more than three hundred thousand foot soldiers, ten thousand horses, and
          twenty thousand chariots (see    5.1.18). Joshua confronted these armies
          and defeated them all with only an infantry and      '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: All these kings and their enormous armies joined forces [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and encamped at Lake Merom  to fight against Israel.
      comments:
      - number: 11:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cmet by appointment.\u201D      Or \u201Cthe waters of
          Merom,\u201D most likely modern Lake Huleh. Josephus called it \u201Cthe
          lake of Semechonitis\u201D (see    5.5.1).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to Joshua, saying, \u201CDon\u2019t
        be afraid of them; by this time tomorrow, I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        will have them all lying slain before Israel. After the battle, cripple their
        horses and burn their chariots.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 11:6
        content: '  did not want Israel to trust in the might of horses or chariots
          but in him alone. See  ;  .    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Joshua launched his surprise attack, and all his army pounced on
        them at their camp at Lake Merom. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> fought [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
        alongside Joshua\u2019s fighting men to defeat them. Part of the Israelite
        army attacked and pursued the retreating forces as far north as the cities
        of Misrephoth Maim  and Sidon.  Another part of the Israelite army pursued
        the enemy as far east as the valley of Mizpah and crushed them all, leaving
        no survivors. "
      comments:
      - number: 11:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cdelivered them into their hands.\u201D        means
          \u201Clime kilns by the waters.\u201D It was a city on the border of Israel
          and Lebanon.      Or \u201CGreat Sidon,\u201D an important Phoenician city
          north of Israel on the Mediterranean coast.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: Afterward, Joshua crippled their horses and burned their chariots
        as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had commanded.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Because Hazor at that time was the most powerful of all these kingdoms,
        Joshua circled back after the battle and conquered it. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cstruck them down with the mouth of the sword.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: They killed the king, burned Hazor [[COMMENT(0)]] to the ground, and
        annihilated all its inhabitants. They spared not one breathing thing, leaving
        no survivors.
      comments:
      - number: 11:11
        content: '  The destruction of Hazor has been dated by recent excavations
          to around 1225 BC. Solomon later rebuilt the city (see  ).    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Joshua conquered all those royal cities and their kings. He destroyed
        them all, as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s servant Moses had commanded. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'However, of all the cities built on mounds, [[COMMENT(0)]] Joshua
        burned down only Hazor. '
      comments:
      - number: 11:13
        content: '  That is, cities that were rebuilt on the ruins of earlier settlements.    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'The Israelites kept all the spoils of these towns, including the
        livestock, but the inhabitants they killed with the sword. There were no
        survivors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: The Territory Taken by Joshua'
      title: The Territory Taken by Joshua
      number: 15
      content: Just as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> commanded his servant Moses,
        so Moses commanded Joshua, and Joshua obeyed everything [[COMMENT(0)]] that
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> commanded Moses.
      comments:
      - number: 11:15
        content: "  The words \u201Cobeyed everything\u201D should be the goal and
          ambition of our lives. Our calling is not simply to be successful but also
          to be obedient. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "So Joshua conquered the entire region: the Judean hills, the southern
        desert, all the land of Goshen, the foothills, the lowlands of the Jordan
        Valley, the northern hill country of Israel including its lowlands\u2014"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: everything from Mount Halak, [[COMMENT(0)]] which rises toward Seir,
        all the way to Baal-Gad  in the Lebanon Valley below Mount Hermon.  Joshua
        captured all their kings and executed them.
      comments:
      - number: 11:17
        content: "    means \u201Cbare mountain\u201D; it is likely Jebel Halaq.       
          means \u201Cthe god of fortune.\u201D      The southern limit of Joshua\u2019s
          conquest was Mount Halak, near Edom, south of the Dead Sea; the northern
          limit was the town of Baal-Gad, not far from Mount Hermon.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Joshua waged war with all those kings over a long period. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:18
        content: "  The \u201Clong period\u201D was about seven years. There are
          spiritual battles we fight that we do not win easily or quickly. Thankfully,
          God will ultimately make us victorious in all things. See  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Apart from the Hivites living in Gibeon, not one city made peace
        with Israel. By the power of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, Joshua conquered
        them all. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> himself hardened their hearts and made
        them obstinate so they would attack Israel. <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        had determined to wipe them out and condemn them to destruction without mercy,
        just as he had commanded Moses.
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Joshua also drove out the Anakim, [[COMMENT(0)]]  a race of giants,
        from the hill country (including the cities of Hebron, Debir, and Anab)\u2014from
        the entire hill country of Judah and Israel. Joshua destroyed the Anakim
        and their towns "
      comments:
      - number: 11:21
        content: "  The Anakim were descendants of Anak. They are mentioned in   
          as intimidating giants that kept the Israelites fearful in unbelief, which
          led to their wandering in the wilderness. Here we read that Joshua eliminated
          these giants and enabled the tribes of Israel to possess their inheritance,
          just as Jesus does today to the giants keeping us from full faith. Giants
          are nothing compared to God\u2019s omnipotence.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'so that there were no surviving Anakim in Israelite territory. Some
        survived but only in the Philistine cities of Gaza, Gath, and Ashdod. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:22
        content: "    means \u201Cfortified\u201D or \u201Cstrength,\u201D    means
          \u201Cwine press,\u201D and    means \u201Cstronghold.\u201D These three
          cities were Philistine cities. The giant Goliath was from Gath (see  ).    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: Joshua conquered the whole land, just as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        had promised Moses. Joshua assigned portions of the land to each of the tribes
        of Israel, and the Israelites lived in peace throughout the land. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 11:23
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe land had rest from war.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Kings Defeated by Moses'
      title: The Kings Defeated by Moses
      number: 1
      content: On the east side of the Jordan, Moses and the Israelites had conquered
        two kings, Sihon and Og. The Israelites occupied their territory, which extended
        from the Arnon Valley in the south to Mount Hermon in the north, including
        the entire eastern desert. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 12:1
        content: "  Or \u201Call the eastern Arabah [dry and desolate area].\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Sihon, king of the Amorites, reigned in Heshbon [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        ruled over the southern half of Gilead, from Aroer on the edge of the Arnon
        River Valley in the south to the River Jabbok in the north, which is the
        border of the Ammonites. '
      comments:
      - number: 12:2
        content: "  Heshbon, the capital city of the Amorites, was about fifteen
          miles northeast of the northern end of the Dead Sea.    means \u201Creasoning\u201D
          or \u201Cstronghold\u201D and hints at the mind of man.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: The western area of his kingdom included the eastern desert from Lake
        Galilee to the Dead Sea (the Salt Sea). His territory included the area east
        of the Dead Sea as far as the town of Beth Jeshimoth [[COMMENT(0)]] and as
        far south as Mount Pisgah.
      comments:
      - number: 12:3
        content: "  Or \u201CHouse of Deserts.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Og, the king of Bashan, [[COMMENT(0)]] was one of the last of the
        race of giants.  He reigned in the cities of Ashtaroth and Edrei.  He ruled
        over all of Bashan, the northern half of Gilead, to the boundary of Sihon,
        king of Heshbon. '
      comments:
      - number: 12:4
        content: "    means \u201Csnake.\u201D It is the region east and northeast
          of Lake Galilee.      Or \u201CRephaites [giants].\u201D For the defeat
          of King Og, see  .      Ashtaroth (also the name of a Canaanite goddess)
          and Edrei are two cities to the east and southeast of Lake Galilee.   
          means \u201Cby force\u201D or \u201Cpower.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'His territory included Mount Hermon in the north and Salecah in the
        east, and south to the boundary of the Geshurites and the Maacathites. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: The Kings Defeated by Joshua'
      title: The Kings Defeated by Joshua
      number: 6
      content: Moses and the Israelites conquered the two kings, Sihon and Og. Moses,
        the servant of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, divided their land east of
        the Jordan among the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and half the tribe of Manasseh.
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "On the west side of the Jordan, Joshua and the Israelites defeated
        thirty-one kings, from Baal-Gad in the Lebanon Valley in the north to Mount
        Halak in the south near Edom. [[COMMENT(0)]] Then Joshua divided this land
        among the tribes of Israel and gave them their portions as permanent possessions\u2014"
      comments:
      - number: 12:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cwhich rises toward Seir,\u201D a mountainous region
          of Edom.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "the hill country, the western foothills, and the Jordan Valley, the
        mountain slopes, the wilderness of Judea, [[COMMENT(0)]] and the southern
        desert region\u2014the land of the Hittites, Amorites, Canaanites, Perizzites,
        Hivites, and Jebusites."
      comments:
      - number: 12:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe eastern slopes.\u201D    "
    - name: '9-24: '
      title: 
      number: 9-24
      content: 'Here is the list of the thirty-one  [[COMMENT(0)]]  kings destroyed
        by Joshua:1. The king of Jericho2. The king of Ai near Bethel3. The king
        of Jerusalem4. The king of Hebron5. The king of Jarmuth6. The king of Lachish7.
        The king of Eglon8. The king of Gezer9. The king of Debir10. The king of
        Geder11. The king of Hormah12. The king of Arad13. The king of Libnah14.
        The king of Adullam15. The king of Makkedah16. The king of Bethel17. The
        king of Tappuah18. The king of Hepher19. The king of Aphek20. The king of
        Lasharon21. The king of Madon22. The king of Hazor23. The king of Shimron
        Meron24. The king of Achshaph25. The king of Taanach26. The king of Megiddo27.
        The king of Kedesh28. The king of Jokneam in Carmel29. The king of Dor on
        the coast30. The king of Goyim  in Galilee31. The king of Tirzah '
      comments:
      - number: "12:9\u201324"
        content: "  The number    is also found in    in reference to the righteous
          reformer King Josiah (similar in Hb. to Joshua) who reigned thirty-one
          years.      The Hebrew word    means \u201Cpeoples.\u201D      Our heavenly
          Joshua (Jesus) has defeated every principality, power, and stronghold that
          resists our advance in Christ. The name of God, El (Mighty God), according
          to its gematria (the numerical value in Jewish culture), equals thirty-one.
          The meaning of the names of the principalities of these thirty-one kings
          could represent the thirty-one strongholds that dull our understanding
          of the finished work of Christ for us: (1) Jericho represents walls, impossibilities,
          limitations. (2)    means \u201Cheap of ruins\u201D (representing the world
          system). (3)    means \u201Clord of righteousness\u201D (counterfeit spirituality,
          under the rule of Adoni-zedek). (4)    means \u201Cfellowship\u201D;   
          means \u201Che crushed\u201D (broken fellowship with God). (5)    means
          \u201Clifted up\u201D;    means \u201Cwild donkey\u201D (pride and arrogance).
          (6)    means \u201Cimpregnable\u201D;    means \u201Csplendid, bright\u201D
          (human ingenuity). (7)    means \u201Cbull-like\u201D (human arguments
          and oratory). (8)    means \u201Csteep, precipitous\u201D (sharp tongue,
          stinging words). (9)    means \u201Cspeaker, oracle\u201D (political spirit).
          (10)    means \u201Cwall\u201D (defensiveness). (11)    means \u201Cdestroyed,
          laid waste\u201D (defeat, depression). (12)    means \u201Cwild fugitive\u201D
          (rebellions, lawlessness). (13)    means \u201Cwhite\u201D (self-righteousness,
          hypocrisy). (14)    means \u201Cjustice of the people\u201D (approval of
          others, insecurity). (15)    means \u201Cplace of shepherds\u201D (false
          shepherds, selfish leadership). (16)    means \u201Chouse of God\u201D
          (religious spirit). (17)    means \u201Capple, distillation\u201D (drunkenness).
          (18)    means \u201Cpit, well\u201D (shame, condemnation). (19)    means
          \u201Cstrength, fortress\u201D (self-sufficiency). (20)    means \u201Clike
          the plain\u201D (complacency, passivity). (21)    means \u201Cstrife, contention\u201D
          (divisive, argumentative). (22)    means \u201Cenclosed, fortified\u201D;   
          means \u201Cintelligent\u201D (human wisdom, mind of man). (23)    means
          \u201Cguardian of arrogance\u201D (traditions, prideful opinions). (24)   
          means \u201Cenchantment\u201D (occult, witchcraft). (25)    means \u201Chard
          to pass, sandy\u201D (soulish, double mindedness). (26)    means \u201Cplace
          of troops, crowded place\u201D (distraction, anxiety). (27)    means \u201Csacred,
          purity\u201D (man-made holiness standards). (28)    means \u201Cpossessed
          by the people\u201D (celebrity worship). (29)    means \u201Cdwelling,
          habitation\u201D (worldly comfort). (30)    means \u201Ccircle\u201D (dull
          of heart, refusing to change, going nowhere). (31)    means \u201Cdelight,
          pleasing\u201D (loving worldly pleasures more than loving God). Jesus sets
          us free from each of these thirty-one strongholds!  "
