  - verses:
    - name: '1: <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> Speaks to Joshua'
      title: <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> Speaks to Joshua
      number: 1
      content: "Many years passed, and Joshua was a very old man. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>.
        Despite all of Joshua\u2019s victories, there remained more territory to
        conquer. Believers today, although complete in Christ, have yet more spiritual
        blessings to possess.</smallcaps> One day, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        spoke to him: \u201CAlthough you have reached a ripe old age, a great deal
        of land remains for you to conquer. "
      comments:
      - number: 13:1
        content: '  Joshua had spied out the land forty-five years earlier (see 
          ). He was over eighty years old at the time of this encounter with      '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'The territory waiting for you to possess includes all the land of
        the Geshurites [[COMMENT(0)]] and the Philistines. (The kings of the Philistines
        lived at Gaza, Ashdod, Ashkelon, Gath, and Ekron.)   '
      comments:
      - number: 13:2
        content: "    means \u201Cthose who see themselves as proud.\u201D These
          people lived in the extreme southwest of Canaan reaching as far south as
          the Egyptian border and are not to be confused with the Geshurites mentioned
          in  .      Philistia consisted of a federation of the five city-states
          mentioned in this verse.    means \u201Cplucked up by the roots.\u201D
          It was on the northeast border of Philistia, possibly the modern village
          of Akar.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'And also all the territory of the Avvites [[COMMENT(0)]] to the south.
        (The land from the stream of Shihor,  at the Egyptian border, as far north
        as the border of Ekron was considered Canaanite.) '
      comments:
      - number: 13:3
        content: "  Or \u201CHivites.\u201D      Some identify Shihor as an eastern
          tributary of the Nile, known as Wadi el-Arish. See  ;  .    means \u201Cdark.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'There is still all the Canaanite territory from the Sidonian city
        of Mearah [[COMMENT(0)]] (which belonged to the Sidonians) as far as the
        Amorite border city of Aphek.   '
      comments:
      - number: 13:4
        content: "    means \u201Ccave.\u201D        means \u201Cstrong enclosure\u201D;
          it was a city northeast of Beirut, Lebanon (modern Aphaca).    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'You have still not conquered the land of the Gebalites, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        all the land eastward to Lebanon, from the city of Baal-Gad, which is south
        of Mount Hermon, to Hamath Pass.   '
      comments:
      - number: 13:5
        content: "    means \u201Cboundary\u201D or \u201Climit\u201D and was also
          known as \u201CBabylus,\u201D a city north of Beirut, Lebanon. Gebal was
          the center of worship of the god Dumuzid, later known as Tammuz.      Or,
          if a proper noun, \u201CLebo Hamath.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'You still must conquer the land of the Sidonians who live in the
        hill country between the Lebanon Mountains and Misrephoth Maim. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        As the people of Israel advance, I myself will drive out these peoples from
        before you! Divide the land among the tribes of Israel exactly as I have
        commanded you. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:6
        content: '  See    and footnote.    '
    - name: '7: The Division of the Land East of the Jordan'
      title: The Division of the Land East of the Jordan
      number: 7
      content: "Divide among the other nine tribes and the other half-tribe of Manasseh
        the territory west of the Jordan to possess as their inheritance.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 13:7
        content: "  The word \u201Cinheritance\u201D is the Hebrew word  , taken
          from the root word  , which has a homonym meaning \u201Ca flowing stream.\u201D
          We can interpret inheritance to mean wealth flowing from one generation
          to the next.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "The tribes of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh had already
        received their portion of the land on the east side of the Jordan, which
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s servant Moses had assigned to them.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 13:8
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'These tribes occupied the land as far southeast as the city of Aroer
        on the edge of the Arnon Valley, including the city in the middle of the
        valley and the plain from Dibon in the south, north to Medeba. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 13:9
        content: '  The Moabites eventually recaptured Dibon and Medeba, the two
          principal towns of Moab.    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Their territory went as far east as the border of Ammon, including
        all the cities over which King Sihon, the Amorite king, ruled over from Heshbon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'It also included Gilead, the land of the Geshurites and Maacathites,
        all of Mount Hermon, and all of Bashan to its eastern boundary of Salecah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'It encompassed the entire kingdom of Og (the last of the Rephaites)
        in Bashan, who ruled from Ashtaroth and at Edrei. Moses had defeated them
        and possessed their lands, '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'except for the Geshurites and Maacathites, who still live among the
        Israelites to this day. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: The Territory Assigned to Reuben'
      title: The Territory Assigned to Reuben
      number: 14
      content: However, Moses did not assign any land as an inheritance to the tribe
        of Levi, for their inheritance was to share in the sacrificial offerings
        [[COMMENT(0)]] made to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of Israel,
        as he promised them.
      comments:
      - number: 13:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cfire offerings.\u201D The people of Israel brought offerings
          to the Levites to support them in their priestly functions. See  .    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The land Moses assigned to the families of the tribe of Reuben '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'extended from Aroer, on the edge of the Arnon Valley, including the
        city in the middle of the valley, the whole plain of Medeba, '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Heshbon and all its surrounding towns on the plain, including Dibon,
        Bamoth Baal, [[COMMENT(0)]] Beth Baal Meon,   '
      comments:
      - number: 13:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe high places of Baal.\u201D      Or \u201Cthe house
          of the lord of Meon,\u201D a likely reference to the local deity worshiped
          at Meon.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Jahaz, [[COMMENT(0)]] Kedemoth, Mephaath, '
      comments:
      - number: 13:18
        content: '  This was the location where Sihon fought with Israel (see  )
          and later became a Levitical city (see  ).    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Kiriathaim, Sibmah, [[COMMENT(0)]] Zereth Shahar on the hill in the
        valley, '
      comments:
      - number: 13:19
        content: '  Sibmah is possibly modern Sumeih.    '
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Beth Peor, the slopes of Pisgah, and Beth Jeshimoth, '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'including all the cities of the plain, and the whole kingdom of Sihon
        the Amorite, who had ruled at Heshbon. Moses defeated him and the Midianite
        tribal chiefs, Evi, Rekem, Zur, Hur, and Reba, who dwelt in the land as princes
        of Sihon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Among those the Israelites killed in battle was the fortune-teller
        Balaam son of Beor. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 13:22
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '23: The Territory Assigned to Gad'
      title: The Territory Assigned to Gad
      number: 23
      content: The western boundary of the Reubenites was the Jordan River. These
        cities and their surrounding villages comprised the inheritance of the families
        of the tribe of Reuben.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'The land Moses assigned to the families of the tribe of Gad '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'included Jazer, all the cities of Gilead, and half the Ammonite country
        as far as Aroer, near Rabbah. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 13:25
        content: "    means \u201Cthe great,\u201D and is the shortened form of Rabbah
          Ammon (modern Amman, Jordan).    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'It extended north from the city of Heshbon to Ramath Mizpah and Betonim,
        continuing on to the city of Mahanaim, and to the borders of Lo-Debar. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 13:26
        content: "  Or \u201CDebir.\u201D See  ;  .    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'In addition, the tribe of Gad received the land along the eastern
        side of the Jordan River as far north as the southern end of Lake Galilee.
        This included the cities of Beth Haram, Beth Nimrah, Sukkoth, and Zaphon,
        all of which were in the Jordan Valley. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: The Territory Assigned to East Manasseh'
      title: The Territory Assigned to East Manasseh
      number: 28
      content: These cities and their surrounding villages comprised the inheritance
        of the families of the tribe of Gad.
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'The land Moses assigned to the families of the half-tribe of Manasseh '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'extended north from the city of Mahanaim, including all of Bashan
        and the sixty villages of Jair. [[COMMENT(0)]] King Og of Bashan had once
        ruled over all this territory. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:30
        content: "    means \u201Cforest\u201D; he was the son (or possibly \u201Cdescendant\u201D)
          of Manasseh. The villages of Jair were villages he conquered (see  ).  "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Moses had given half of Gilead to this half-tribe of Manasseh, which
        descended from Manasseh\u2019s son Machir, including the cities of Ashtaroth
        and Edrei, where king Og had once ruled."
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'Moses had distributed all the territory of Moab in the Jordan Valley
        east of Jericho as the inheritances of these two and a half tribes of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "But Moses gave no inheritance of land to the tribe of Levi, but said
        to them, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, is to be
        your inheritance.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Division of the Land West of the Jordan'
      title: The Division of the Land West of the Jordan
      number: 1
      content: 'Eleazar the priest, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> Joshua
        son of Nun, and the Israelite tribal leaders divided the land west of the
        Jordan among the people of Israel as their inheritance. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:1
        content: "  Eleazar was the son and successor of Aaron (see  ).  had instructed
          Moses to include the tribal leaders in the allotment of land to the Israelites.
          See  . Eleazar was mentioned before Joshua because the high priest presided
          over the drawing of lots, for he bore the Urim and Thummim on his breastplate.
          A traditional account of this event is stated in the Talmud: \u201CEleazar
          was wearing the Urim and Thummim, while Joshua and all Israel stood before
          him. An urn containing the names of the tribes and an urn containing descriptions
          of the boundaries were placed before him. Animated by the Holy Spirit,
          he gave directions, exclaiming, \u2018Zebulun is coming up and boundaries
          of Acco came up with it.\u2019 Thereupon, he shook well the urn of the
          tribes and Zebulun came up in his hand. Likewise, he shook well the urn
          of the boundaries and boundary of the line of Acco came up in his hand;
          .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;and so with the other tribes.\u201D (See Bava Batra
          122a.)    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'By drawing lots, Eleazar assigned territory to the nine and a half
        tribes, as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had commanded Moses. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 14:2
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '3-4: '
      title: 
      number: 3-4
      content: 'The descendants of Joseph were divided into two tribes, Manasseh
        and Ephraim. Moses had already granted land east of the Jordan, but the tribe
        of Levi did not receive land as their inheritance. However, they were assigned
        cities in which to live and pasturelands for their property and livestock.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: "14:3\u20134"
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '3-4: '
      title: 
      number: 3-4
      content: 'The descendants of Joseph were divided into two tribes, Manasseh
        and Ephraim. Moses had already granted land east of the Jordan, but the tribe
        of Levi did not receive land as their inheritance. However, they were assigned
        cities in which to live and pasturelands for their property and livestock.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: "14:3\u20134"
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '5: Caleb'
      title: Caleb
      number: 5
      content: So the Israelites divided the land as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        had commanded Moses.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "One day, while Israel was encamped at Gilgal, the people of Judah
        approached Joshua, including Caleb [[COMMENT(0)]] son of Jephunneh  from
        the Kenizzite  clan. Caleb said to Joshua, \u201CRemember what <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        said to Moses about you and me while we were still at Kadesh Barnea. "
      comments:
      - number: 14:6
        content: "  The name    can be translated \u201Cdog.\u201D However, because
          the name is actually a compound word in Hebrew, alternate meanings are
          \u201Cfaithful,\u201D \u201Cdevoted,\u201D \u201Cwholehearted,\u201D \u201Cbold,\u201D
          and \u201Cbrave.\u201D        means \u201Che will behold.\u201D       
          (see  ) means \u201Cpossessor,\u201D \u201Cspear-thrower,\u201D or \u201Chunter.\u201D
          The descendants of Kenaz (Kenizzites), a non-Israelite people group, were
          later incorporated into the Judahite genealogy (see  ).    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "I was forty years old when Moses, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servant, sent me from Kadesh Barnea to spy out the land of Canaan, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and I brought back an honest and accurate report.   "
      comments:
      - number: 14:7
        content: "  See  .      Or \u201Cas it was in my heart\u201D or \u201Caccording
          to my convictions.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "I have been faithful and obedient to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        my God. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>, my God.\u201D</smallcaps> But my fellow
        spies who went with me only discouraged the people and made their hearts
        shrink back with fear. "
      comments:
      - number: 14:8
        content: "  Or \u201CI filled [myself] up with      "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "On that day, Moses made an oath and promised me, \u2018Every part
        of the land your feet tread upon shall be an inheritance for you and your
        descendants forever because you were loyal to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        my God.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 14:9
        content: '  See  ,  . Inheritance is based on obedience to the Lord.    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CSo here I am. It\u2019s been forty-five years since <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        made this promise to Moses, when Israel journeyed through the wilderness.
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has preserved me, an eighty-five-year-old man,
        to this day. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "I\u2019m still as strong today as on that day when Moses sent me
        out! I\u2019m just as fit to go out to battle now as I was then. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Now give me the hill country that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> promised
        me on that day. You yourself were there and heard the report that the Anakim
        lived there in strong and fortified cities. I know that with the power of
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> helping me, I will drive them out, just as
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 14:12
        content: "  Caleb\u2019s courage at eighty-five was incredible! He was neither
          weary nor intimidated by any giant. He knew God had promised him that land,
          and no giant was going to get in his way. Caleb was a giant-killer. Some
          scholars believe that he lived another twenty-five years enjoying his inheritance.  "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Joshua spoke God\u2019s blessing over Caleb son of Jephunneh and
        gave him Hebron as his inheritance. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'So Hebron has belonged to Caleb son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite ever
        since because he passionately followed <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the
        God of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: (Hebron used to be called the City of Arba, after Arba, the most famous
        of all the Anakim.) Then the land was free of war.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Judah\u2019s Inheritance"
      title: "Judah\u2019s Inheritance"
      number: 1
      content: 'Here is the land allotted to the families of the tribe of Judah:
        Their territory extended southward to the Wilderness of Zin, which belonged
        to Edom. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Their boundary started from the bay at the southern end of the Dead
        Sea, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'crossed south of Scorpion Pass, continued to Zin, and went on south
        of Kadesh Barnea. Then it went past Hezron up to Addar and curved around
        to Karka, '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: continued to Azmon and followed the stream on the border of Egypt
        in a northwesterly direction to the Mediterranean Sea. That is the southern
        border of all the tribes of Israel.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The Dead Sea formed the eastern border of Judah, and its territory
        lay to the west toward the Mediterranean Sea. Their northern border began
        there '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "and went up to Beth Hoglah and continued north of the ridge overlooking
        the Jordan Valley. [[COMMENT(0)]] From there it went up to the Stone of Bohan,
        named after Bohan, Reuben\u2019s son. "
      comments:
      - number: 15:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cnorth of Beth Arabah.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'The boundary then went up to Debir from the Valley of Achor [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and turned north to Gilgal, which faces Adummim Pass south of the gorge.
        It continued along to the waters of En Shemesh and ended at En Rogel. '
      comments:
      - number: 15:7
        content: "  Or \u201CValley of Trouble.\u201D    (Achan) means \u201Ctrouble.\u201D
          See  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Then the boundary ran through the Hinnom Valley along the southern
        slope of Jebus (now known as Jerusalem). From there it went to the top of
        the hill west of the Hinnom Valley at the northern end of the Valley of Rephaites.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 15:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Valley of the Giants.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'It continued from the top of the mountain to the spring of the waters
        of Nephtoah, and from there to the town of Mount Ephron and on to Baalah,
        which today is called Kiriath Jearim. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'It then turned west from Baalah to Mount Seir and ran along the northern
        shoulder of Mount Jearim (that is, Kesalon), descended to the city of Beth
        Shemesh, and crossed to the city of Timnah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: The border then went north to the ridge of the city of Ekron, turned
        toward the city of Shikkeron, crossed to Mount Baalah, and came out at the
        city of Jamnia. [[COMMENT(0)]] The border ended at the southern end of the
        Dead Sea.
      comments:
      - number: 15:11
        content: "  Or \u201CJabneel.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: Caleb Conquers Hebron and Debir'
      title: Caleb Conquers Hebron and Debir
      number: 12
      content: The western boundary was the Mediterranean coastline. This was the
        territory that belonged to the families of the tribe of Judah.
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had commanded Joshua, \u201CGive a
        share of the territory from the tribe of Judah to Caleb son of Jephunneh.\u201D
        So Joshua gave him the city of Hebron which was founded by Arba, the ancestor
        of Anak. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Caleb drove out three Anakim from Hebron: Sheshai, Ahiman, and Talmai\u2014descendants
        of Anak. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 15:14
        content: "  The descendants of Anak were the giants in the land.    means
          \u201Cwhitewashed\u201D; he represents hypocrisy. Jesus called the religious
          scholars of his day and the Pharisees hypocrites and \u201Ctombs painted
          over with white paint\u201D ().    means \u201Cbrother of my right hand\u201D
          or \u201Cmy brother is a gift\u201D; he represents an exaggerated spirituality.   
          means \u201Cbrave\u201D; he represents arrogance and false confidence.
          If we find these giants in the \u201Cland\u201D of our hearts, then we
          must cast them out.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: From Hebron, he marched out and fought against the people of Debir,
        which used to be called Kiriath Sepher.
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Caleb once promised, \u201CWhoever succeeds in capturing Kiriath
        Sepher [[COMMENT(0)]] may marry my daughter Achsah.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 15:16
        content: "    means \u201Cthe city of the book.\u201D    (v.  ) means \u201Coracle\u201D
          or \u201Cthe word of God.\u201D The one who conquers \u201CBook City\u201D
          and changes it to the \u201Cword of God\u201D will get the daughter of
          Caleb.    means \u201Canklet\u201D (beautiful feet of the evangelist, see 
          ).    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Caleb\u2019s nephew Othniel, the son of his brother Kenaz, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        took the city, so Caleb gave him the hand of his daughter Achsah in marriage."
      comments:
      - number: 15:17
        content: "  Kenaz was possibly Caleb\u2019s half brother.    means \u201Clion
          of God\u201D; this nephew of Caleb became the first \u201Cdeliverer\u201D
          or \u201Cjudge.\u201D See  .    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "One day, Achsah came and charmed her father so that she could ask
        him for a gift. When she got down from her donkey, Caleb said to her, \u201CWhat
        would you like for a wedding present?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: The Cities of Judah'
      title: The Cities of Judah
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CFather,\u201D she replied, \u201Cgive me a special gift. You
        have already given me land, but it\u2019s in arid country. Please, also give
        me some springs of water.\u201D So Caleb gave her the upper and lower springs
        near the city of Hebron."
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'These are the cities given as an inheritance to the families of the
        tribe of Judah. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 15:20
        content: '  From here through ch.  , Joshua gives us detailed geographical
          descriptions of the inheritances of the tribes of Israel. Many of the places
          mentioned are never referenced again in Scripture, thus making them difficult
          to identify. Judah is mentioned first, for it was the leader-tribe of Israel.
          See  ;  .    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: The cities of the first district in the extreme south near the border
        of Edom includedKabzeel, Eder, Jagur,
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: Kinah, Dimonah, Adadah,
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: Kedesh, Hazor, Ithnan,
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: Ziph, Telem, Bealoth,
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: Hazor Hadattah, Kerioth Hezron (that is, Hazor),
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: Amam, Shema, Moladah,
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: Hazar Gaddah, Heshmon, Beth Pelet,
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: Hazar Shual, Beersheba, Biziothiah,
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: Baalah, Iyyim, Ezem,
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: Eltolad, Kesil, Hormah,
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: Ziklag, Madmannah, Sansannah,
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Lebaoth, Shilhim, Ain, and Rimmon\u2014a total of twenty-nine towns
        and their villages."
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: The cities of the second district in the western foothills includedEshtaol,
        Zorah, Ashnah,
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: Zanoah, En Gannim, Tappuah, Enam,
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: Jarmuth, Adullam, Socoh, Azekah,
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Shaaraim, Adithaim, and Gederah (or Gederothaim) [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014fourteen
        towns and their villages."
      comments:
      - number: 15:36
        content: "  Or \u201Cand its sheepfolds,\u201D which would make a total of
          fourteen cities.    "
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: The cities of the third district includedZenan, Hadashah, Migdal Gad,
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: Dilean, Mizpah, Joktheel,
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: Lachish, Bozkath, Eglon,
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: Cabbon, Lahmas, Kitlish,
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "Gederoth, Beth Dagon, Naamah, and Makkedah\u2014sixteen towns and
        their villages."
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: The cities of the fourth district includedLibnah, Ether, Ashan,
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: Iphtah, Ashnah, Nezib,
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "Keilah, Aczib, and Mareshah\u2014nine towns and their villages."
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: The cities of the fifth district includedEkron, with its surrounding
        settlements and villages;
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: from Ekron westward, all the towns in the vicinity of Ashdod, together
        with their villages;
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: Ashdod, and its surrounding settlements and villages;and Gaza, its
        settlements and villages, as far south as the Wadi of Egypt and as far west
        as the coastline of the Mediterranean Sea.
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: The cities of the sixth district in the Judean hills includedShamir,
        Jattir, Socoh,
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: Dannah, Kiriath Sannah (that is, Debir),
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: Anab, Eshtemoh, Anim, [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 15:50
        content: "  The Septuagint adds another district at the end of verse  , as
          follows: \u201CTekoa, Ephrath (that is, Bethlehem), Peor, Etam, Culon,
          Tatam, Shoresh, Cerem, Gallim, Bether, and Manach: eleven cities, along
          with the towns around them.\u201D Many scholars believe that the Septuagint
          preserves the original text here. Some modern translations include the
          addition.    "
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "Goshen, Holon, and Giloh\u2014eleven towns and their villages."
      comments: []
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: The cities of the seventh district includedArab, Dumah, Eshan,
      comments: []
    - name: '53: '
      title: 
      number: 53
      content: Janim, Beth Tappuah, Aphekah,
      comments: []
    - name: '54: '
      title: 
      number: 54
      content: "Humtah, Kiriath Arba (that is, Hebron), and Zior\u2014nine towns
        and their villages."
      comments: []
    - name: '55: '
      title: 
      number: 55
      content: The cities of the eighth district includedMaon, Carmel, Ziph, Juttah,
      comments: []
    - name: '56: '
      title: 
      number: 56
      content: Jezreel, Jokdeam, Zanoah,
      comments: []
    - name: '57: '
      title: 
      number: 57
      content: "Kain, Gibeah, and Timnah\u2014ten towns and their villages."
      comments: []
    - name: '58: '
      title: 
      number: 58
      content: The cities of the ninth district includedHalhul, Beth Zur, Gedor,
      comments: []
    - name: '59: '
      title: 
      number: 59
      content: "Maarath, Beth Anoth, and Eltekon\u2014six towns and their villages."
      comments: []
    - name: '60: '
      title: 
      number: 60
      content: "The cities of the tenth district includedKiriath Baal (that is, Kiriath
        Jearim) and Rabbah\u2014two towns and their villages."
      comments: []
    - name: '61: '
      title: 
      number: 61
      content: The desert cities of the eleventh district includedBeth Arabah, Middin,
        Secacah,
      comments: []
    - name: '62: '
      title: 
      number: 62
      content: "Nibshan, the City of Salt, [[COMMENT(0)]] and En Gedi\u2014six towns
        and their villages. "
      comments:
      - number: 15:62
        content: "  The Hebrew is  , possibly in later times the site of the Qumran
          community of Essenes.      There are 110 cities mentioned in this chapter,
          one city for every year of Joshua\u2019s life. See  .  "
    - name: '63: '
      title: 
      number: 63
      content: The people of Judah could not dislodge the Jebusites from Jerusalem,
        and they live among the people of Judah to this day.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: The Land Given to Joseph\u2019s Descendants"
      title: "The Land Given to Joseph\u2019s Descendants"
      number: 1
      content: "The territory assigned to Joseph\u2019s descendants began east of
        the springs of Jericho near the Jordan, then turned north through the desert
        and into the hill country as far as Bethel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'From Bethel (that is, Luz), [[COMMENT(0)]] it crossed over to Arkite 
        territory at Ataroth.   '
      comments:
      - number: 16:2
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint. The Hebrew reads \u201CFrom
          Bethel to Luz.\u201D      The Arkites were descendants of Arki, a son of
          Canaan and grandson of Ham (see  ).      Or \u201CAtaroth Addar.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'It then descended westward to the territory of the Japhletites as
        far as the border of Lower Beth Horon and Gezer, ending at the Mediterranean
        Sea. '
      comments: []
    - name: "4: The Land Given to Ephraim\u2019s Descendants"
      title: "The Land Given to Ephraim\u2019s Descendants"
      number: 4
      content: Ephraim and Manasseh, the descendants of Joseph, inherited this entire
        territory.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The southern boundary of the territory of the tribe of Ephraim went
        from Ataroth Addar in the east to Upper Beth Horon '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'then westward to the Sea. The northern boundary went from Michmethath
        to the east of Taanath-Shiloh and going further to the east of Janoah. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 16:6
        content: '  Scholars identify Janoah with modern Yanun, eight miles southeast
          of Nablus.    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'From Janoah the border descended to Ataroth and Naarah. It touched
        Jericho and came out at the Jordan River. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8-9: '
      title: 
      number: 8-9
      content: 'From Tappuah, it proceeded westward to the Kanah Ravine and ended
        at the Sea. The inheritance of the families of the tribe of Ephraim also
        included the towns and villages set apart for them within the territory of
        West Manasseh. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: "16:8\u20139"
        content: '  See  .  '
    - name: '8-9: '
      title: 
      number: 8-9
      content: 'From Tappuah, it proceeded westward to the Kanah Ravine and ended
        at the Sea. The inheritance of the families of the tribe of Ephraim also
        included the towns and villages set apart for them within the territory of
        West Manasseh. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: "16:8\u20139"
        content: '  See  .  '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: However, the Ephraimites did not drive out the Canaanites from the
        city of Gezer, but they conscripted the Canaanites to serve them to this
        day.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Half-Tribe of West Manasseh'
      title: The Half-Tribe of West Manasseh
      number: 1
      content: "Joshua assigned land to the descendants of Manasseh, Joseph\u2019s
        firstborn son. Joshua allotted Gilead and Bashan to Machir the firstborn
        of Manasseh, the father of Gilead, because he was a brave warrior. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: And Joshua assigned land west of the Jordan River to the rest of the
        tribe of Manasseh. The male descendants of Manasseh were Abiezer, Helek,
        Asriel, Shechem, Hepher, and Shemida. All of these men were heads of families,
        and each of their families received territory west of the Jordan River.
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Manasseh\u2019s grandson Gilead had a son named Hepher who had a
        son named Zelophehad, [[COMMENT(0)]] who had no sons.  But he did have five
        daughters: Mahlah,  Noah,  Hoglah,  Milcah,  and Tirzah.   "
      comments:
      - number: 17:3
        content: "    means \u201Cfirst one [to break through]\u201D or \u201Cfirstborn.\u201D     
          See  .        means \u201Csmooth,\u201D \u201Cpolished,\u201D \u201Ccaressing,\u201D
          or \u201Cpleasing.\u201D        is found here as a woman\u2019s name and
          means \u201Crest,\u201D \u201Ccall,\u201D \u201Cquiet,\u201D or \u201Cpeace.\u201D       
          means \u201Chopping bird\u201D or \u201Cquail.\u201D        means \u201Cqueen,\u201D
          \u201Crule,\u201D or \u201Ccounsel.\u201D        means \u201Cpleasure,\u201D
          \u201Cdelight,\u201D \u201Cloving,\u201D or \u201Cgraciousness.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "They came before the priest Eleazar and Joshua son of Nun and the
        leaders, and said, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> commanded Moses to
        give us an inheritance among our relatives.\u201D So according to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        commandment, he gave an inheritance to them as he did to their uncles. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5-6: '
      title: 
      number: 5-6
      content: "Since Joshua assigned land to both Manasseh\u2019s male and female
        descendants, the tribe of Manasseh received ten shares of land on the west
        side of the Jordan River and two on the east (the territories of Gilead and
        Bashan)."
      comments: []
    - name: '5-6: '
      title: 
      number: 5-6
      content: "Since Joshua assigned land to both Manasseh\u2019s male and female
        descendants, the tribe of Manasseh received ten shares of land on the west
        side of the Jordan River and two on the east (the territories of Gilead and
        Bashan)."
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'The northwest territory of Manasseh reached from Asher to Michmethath,
        which is east of Shechem; the boundary went southward to the inhabitants
        of the spring of Tappuah [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 17:7
        content: "    means \u201Capple.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'and divided the land of Tappuah belonging to the tribe of Manasseh
        from the town of Tappuah belonging to the Ephraimites. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: 'From there, the southern border followed the Kanah Stream westward
        to the Mediterranean Sea. The main territory of Manasseh lay north of the
        stream of Kanah, but south of it were some cities that belonged to the tribe
        of Ephraim even though they were located inside the territory of Manasseh.
        In the northwest, Manasseh bordered on the tribe of Asher, and in the northeast,
        it bordered on the tribe of Issachar. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: 'From there, the southern border followed the Kanah Stream westward
        to the Mediterranean Sea. The main territory of Manasseh lay north of the
        stream of Kanah, but south of it were some cities that belonged to the tribe
        of Ephraim even though they were located inside the territory of Manasseh.
        In the northwest, Manasseh bordered on the tribe of Asher, and in the northeast,
        it bordered on the tribe of Issachar. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Within these two territories, there were several cities together
        with their surrounding towns that belonged to Manasseh: Beth Shean, Ibleam,
        Dor, Endor, Taanach, and Megiddo. These constituted three regions. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 17:11
        content: '  The Hebrew meaning is uncertain.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Yet the men of Manasseh failed to take possession of those towns,
        and the Canaanites continued to live in that land. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: The Tribes of Ephraim and West Manasseh Request More Land'
      title: The Tribes of Ephraim and West Manasseh Request More Land
      number: 13
      content: Later, when the Israelites grew strong, they put the Canaanites to
        forced labor but did not utterly drive them out.
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "One day, the descendants of Joseph came to Joshua and said, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has blessed us with many people, but you have given us only one part of the
        land. We ought to have more land!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Joshua said to them, \u201CIf the hill country of Ephraim is too
        small for the large number of people in your tribes, then go into the forests
        which belong to the Perizzites and the Rephaites, and clear ground for yourselves
        there.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "The descendants of Joseph answered, \u201CIndeed, there\u2019s not
        enough room for us in the hill country of Ephraim. Yet all the Canaanites
        who live in the plain have chariots with iron-rimmed wheels, both those in
        Beth Shean and its villages, and those in the Valley of Jezreel.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Then Joshua said to the tribe of Ephraim and the half-tribe of Manasseh,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CThere are indeed many people in your tribes, and for
        that reason, you are very powerful. I will give you more than one share of
        land. "
      comments:
      - number: 17:17
        content: "  Or \u201CThen Joshua said to the house of Joseph.\u201D  "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Therefore, I will give you the hill country as well. It is a forest,
        but <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  will empower you to take possession of
        it and clear it from one end to the other. You will conquer all the Canaanites
        even though they not only have iron chariots but also are a strong people.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Tabernacle at Shiloh'
      title: The Tabernacle at Shiloh
      number: 1
      content: 'After the Israelites had conquered the land, all of them gathered
        at Shiloh, [[COMMENT(0)]] and the priests set up the tabernacle. '
      comments:
      - number: 18:1
        content: "  After seven years of conquest, the Israelites moved the tabernacle
          that Moses had constructed in the wilderness from Gilgal to Shiloh, where
          it remained for 369 years. Shiloh became the center of worship throughout
          the time of the Judges (also the time of the book of Ruth).    means \u201Cwhole,\u201D
          \u201Csound,\u201D \u201Cquiet,\u201D \u201Csecure,\u201D \u201Chealth,\u201D
          or \u201Cabundance.\u201D It was the place where Hannah prayed to have
          a son and then dedicated her miracle son, Samuel, to God (see  ). He became
          the first of the prophets of Israel. The origins of the prophets can be
          traced back to the ancient pre-Jerusalem capital of Israel, Shiloh. See 
          ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  . Jesus is our Shiloh (see  ).    "
    - name: '2-3: '
      title: 
      number: 2-3
      content: "Joshua addressed the seven tribes that remained [[COMMENT(0)]] who
        had not yet received their inheritance: \u201CHow much more time will you
        waste until you go out and possess the land that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the God of your ancestors, has given you? "
      comments:
      - number: "18:2\u20133"
        content: "  Judah plus Gad, Reuben, and the (eastern) half-tribe of Manasseh
          were the four tribes so far possessing their inheritance. Benjamin (see
          vv.  ), Simeon (see  ), Zebulun (see  ), Issachar (see  ), Naphtali (see 
          ), and Dan (see  ) were the \u201Cremaining seven\u201D tribes. Levi, of
          course, did not inherit land (see vv.  ). In addition, Joshua inherited
          a city, Timnath Serah (see  ).    "
