    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The one who has committed manslaughter shall escape for protection
        to one of these cities and stand at the entrance to the city gates and explain
        his case to the leaders of the city. The leaders must then receive him into
        their city and grant him asylum. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'When the one looking for revenge [[COMMENT(0)]] comes after him,
        the leaders of the city must protect him and not hand him over, for he killed
        the person accidentally and without premeditation. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe blood-redeemer,\u201D that is, a relative of the
          one killed. See  . The avenger of blood is a picture of the law (see  ; 
          ;  ;  ).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "He must remain in the city until he has had a public trial; then
        he must remain protected in the city until the man who is high priest at
        that time has died. Afterward, he may return to his family and his own hometown.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 20:6
        content: "  The protection of the manslayer would be based on the killer
          being proven innocent (accidental death). If found innocent, he would remain
          in the city until the death of the ruling high priest. See  ,  . After
          the high priest\u2019s death, the manslayer would receive amnesty and permission
          to return home. However, if he were found guilty of premeditated murder,
          there was no protection for him\u2014the leaders would turn him over to
          the avenging relative of the dead man. See  .    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'So they dedicated three cities on the west side of the Jordan River:
        Kedesh in Galilee in the hill country of Naphtali, Shechem in the hill country
        of Ephraim, and Kiriath Arba (that is, Hebron) in the hill country of Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'And beyond the Jordan east of Jericho, they dedicated Bezer in the
        desert plain belonging to the tribe of Reuben, Ramoth in Gilead, from the
        tribe of Gad, and Golan in Bashan, from the tribe of Manasseh. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 20:8
        content: '  Although Moses had already designated these three cities east
          of the Jordan (see  ), they were not officially appointed until Joshua
          had the people of Israel select three cities on the west side of the Jordan
          River.    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: These were the designated cities of refuge. [[COMMENT(0)]] Any Israelite
        or any foreigner  living among them who had accidentally killed someone could
        run to one of these cities for protection. He could live there safely until
        he had a fair trial, and unless he had been proven guilty, he could not be
        killed by the one seeking revenge.
      comments:
      - number: 20:9
        content: "  The six cities of asylum all point to Christ and his tender mercy
          (see  ;  ;  ;  ). The positioning of these six cities was meant to provide
          access to everyone from wherever they lived. They built roads to these
          cities to help the one fleeing from vengeance. See  . The cities of refuge
          were situated on hills and high places so that the manslayer could easily
          see them and find them. Similarly, Jesus has been exalted to the highest
          place as our Champion and Savior, and yet he is accessible to all by faith.   
          means \u201Ccut off,\u201D \u201Cfortification,\u201D or \u201Cstrong city,\u201D
          and speaks of Christ as our secure refuge.    means \u201Cexaltation\u201D
          or \u201Cheavenly,\u201D and speaks of Christ as our high and exalted refuge.   
          means \u201Ctheir rejoicing\u201D (see  ), and speaks of Christ as our
          perfect refuge.    means \u201Choly place,\u201D \u201Csacred,\u201D \u201Csanctified,\u201D
          or \u201Choliness\u201D (see  ), and speaks of Christ as our holy refuge.   
          means \u201Cbetween the shoulders,\u201D \u201Cburden bearer,\u201D or
          \u201Cstrength,\u201D and speaks of Christ as our strong refuge (see  ; 
          ).    means \u201Cunited,\u201D \u201Cfellowship,\u201D \u201Cjoined,\u201D
          or \u201Ccommunion\u201D and speaks of Christ as our loving refuge who
          has joined himself to us. We are safe forever, for our High Priest will
          never die. See  .      These refuge cities were to be available for all,
          even the gentiles (see  ;  ).  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1-2: The Cities of the Levites'
      title: The Cities of the Levites
      number: 1-2
      content: "While the people of Israel camped at Shiloh in the land of Canaan,
        the ancestral heads of the Levites went to Eleazar the priest, to Joshua
        son of Nun, and to the heads of the families of all of the tribes of Israel
        and said, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> instructed through Moses for
        you to give us cities to live in and pasturelands around the cities for our
        livestock.\u201D "
      comments: []
