    - name: '17-18: '
      title: 
      number: 17-18
      content: 'They received four cities from the territory of Benjamin: Gibeon,
        Geba, Anathoth, and Almon, along with the pastureland of each. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: The priests, the descendants of Aaron, received thirteen cities in
        all, with their pasturelands.
      comments: []
    - name: '20-22: '
      title: 
      number: 20-22
      content: The rest of the Kohathite clans of Levi received four cities with
        their pasturelands in the territory of Ephraim. One of these cities was Shechem,
        located in the hill country and one of the cities of asylum. The other three
        cities were Gezer, Kibzaim, and Beth Horon.
      comments: []
    - name: '20-22: '
      title: 
      number: 20-22
      content: The rest of the Kohathite clans of Levi received four cities with
        their pasturelands in the territory of Ephraim. One of these cities was Shechem,
        located in the hill country and one of the cities of asylum. The other three
        cities were Gezer, Kibzaim, and Beth Horon.
      comments: []
    - name: '20-22: '
      title: 
      number: 20-22
      content: The rest of the Kohathite clans of Levi received four cities with
        their pasturelands in the territory of Ephraim. One of these cities was Shechem,
        located in the hill country and one of the cities of asylum. The other three
        cities were Gezer, Kibzaim, and Beth Horon.
      comments: []
    - name: '23-24: '
      title: 
      number: 23-24
      content: 'The Levites also received four cities from the territory of Dan:
        Eltekeh, Gibbethon, Aijalon, and Gath Rimmon, along with the pastureland
        of each.'
      comments: []
    - name: '23-24: '
      title: 
      number: 23-24
      content: 'The Levites also received four cities from the territory of Dan:
        Eltekeh, Gibbethon, Aijalon, and Gath Rimmon, along with the pastureland
        of each.'
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'They also received two cities from the half-tribe of Manasseh: Taanach
        and Gath Rimmon, along with the pastureland of each. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: The rest of the Kohathite clans received ten towns and their pasturelands.
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'The Levite clans of the Gershonites received two towns from the half-tribe
        of Manasseh: Golan in Bashan (a city of asylum for one who committed manslaughter)
        and Beeshterah, together with their pasturelands.'
      comments: []
    - name: '28-29: '
      title: 
      number: 28-29
      content: 'They received four towns from the tribe of Issachar: Kishion, Daberath,
        Jarmuth, and En Gannim, together with their pasturelands.'
      comments: []
    - name: '28-29: '
      title: 
      number: 28-29
      content: 'They received four towns from the tribe of Issachar: Kishion, Daberath,
        Jarmuth, and En Gannim, together with their pasturelands.'
      comments: []
    - name: '30-31: '
      title: 
      number: 30-31
      content: 'They received four towns from the tribe of Asher: Mishal, Abdon,
        Helkath, and Rehob, together with their pasturelands.'
      comments: []
    - name: '30-31: '
      title: 
      number: 30-31
      content: 'They received four towns from the tribe of Asher: Mishal, Abdon,
        Helkath, and Rehob, together with their pasturelands.'
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'They received three towns from the tribe of Naphtali: Kedesh in Galilee
        (a city of asylum for one who committed manslaughter), Hammoth Dor, and Kartan,
        together with their pasturelands. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: All the Gershonite clans received thirteen towns, together with their
        pasturelands.
      comments: []
    - name: '34-35: '
      title: 
      number: 34-35
      content: 'The remaining Levites of the Merarite clans received four cities
        from the tribe of Zebulun: Jokneam, Kartah, Dimnah, and Nahalal, along with
        the pastureland of each.'
      comments: []
    - name: '34-35: '
      title: 
      number: 34-35
      content: 'The remaining Levites of the Merarite clans received four cities
        from the tribe of Zebulun: Jokneam, Kartah, Dimnah, and Nahalal, along with
        the pastureland of each.'
      comments: []
    - name: '36-37: '
      title: 
      number: 36-37
      content: 'They received four cities from the tribe of Reuben: Bezer, Jahaz,
        Kedemoth, and Mephaath, along with the pastureland of each.'
      comments: []
    - name: '36-37: '
      title: 
      number: 36-37
      content: 'They received four cities from the tribe of Reuben: Bezer, Jahaz,
        Kedemoth, and Mephaath, along with the pastureland of each.'
      comments: []
    - name: '38-39: '
      title: 
      number: 38-39
      content: 'They received four cities from the tribe of Gad: Ramoth in Gilead
        (a city of asylum for one who committed manslaughter), Mahanaim, Heshbon,
        and Jazer, along with the pastureland of each. '
      comments: []
    - name: '38-39: '
      title: 
      number: 38-39
      content: 'They received four cities from the tribe of Gad: Ramoth in Gilead
        (a city of asylum for one who committed manslaughter), Mahanaim, Heshbon,
        and Jazer, along with the pastureland of each. '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: Merarite clans of the remaining Levites received twelve cities in
        all.
      comments: []
    - name: '41-42: Israel Takes Possession of the Land'
      title: Israel Takes Possession of the Land
      number: 41-42
      content: The Levites received from the other tribes of Israel a total of forty-eight
        cities, each with the pasturelands around them.
      comments: []
    - name: '41-42: Israel Takes Possession of the Land'
      title: Israel Takes Possession of the Land
      number: 41-42
      content: The Levites received from the other tribes of Israel a total of forty-eight
        cities, each with the pasturelands around them.
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'So <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> gave Israel all the land he had
        promised their ancestors. They took possession of the land and settled there. '
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> kept his promise and gave them peace
        in the land [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> just as he had promised
        to their forefathers. Not one of their enemies could stand against them. '
      comments:
      - number: 21:44
        content: "  Or \u201Cgave them rest on every side.\u201D See  .  "
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> didn\u2019t break a single promise
        that he made to the people of Israel. He faithfully kept every promise he
        made to them."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Eastern Tribes Return to Their Land'
      title: The Eastern Tribes Return to Their Land
      number: 1
      content: 'Then Joshua summoned all the men of the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and
        East Manasseh '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "and said to them, \u201CYou have done all that Moses the servant
        of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> commanded, and you have obeyed me in everything
        I commanded. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Through it all, you\u2019ve never deserted your fellow Israelites
        and were always there to help them. You\u2019ve completed every task given
        to you by <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Yes, he has promised peace to your fellow Israelites, and he has
        kept that promise. So now, return to the homeland east of the Jordan which
        Moses, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s servant, assigned to you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Make sure you obey every command and instruction Moses, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servant, gave you. Love <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>! He is your God, so
        walk in his ways and obey his commands! Cling to him and serve him diligently
        with all your heart and with all your soul!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Then Joshua spoke a blessing over them and sent them on their way,
        and they settled there. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 22:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cthey went to their tents.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'To one half of the tribe of Manasseh, Moses had assigned land in
        Bashan. To the other half, Joshua assigned land on the west side of the Jordan
        with their fellow Israelites. Joshua blessed them and sent them off to their
        homes '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "with these words: \u201CYou are free to go. You leave for your homes
        rich\u2014with great herds of cattle, silver and gold, bronze and iron, and
        a great quantity of clothing! Share with your friends and families everything
        you took from your enemies.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: The Tribes East of the Jordan Build an Altar'
      title: The Tribes East of the Jordan Build an Altar
      number: 9
      content: "So the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and East Manasseh left their fellow
        Israelites at Shiloh in Canaan and returned to Gilead, their homeland. For
        Moses had told them before he died, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> wants
        you to take this land for your own.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'On their way home, the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and East Manasseh came
        to the town of Geliloth near the Jordan River. So they built their own large,
        impressive altar there. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 22:10
        content: '  The Hebrew text is somewhat ambiguous. Although some scholars
          (including the historian Josephus) believe the altar was on the east side
          of the river, it is more likely they built it on the west bank before they
          crossed over.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'When the rest of the Israelites heard that the people of the tribe
        of Reuben, Gad, and East Manasseh had built an altar at Geliloth at the entrance
        to the land of Canaan, '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: they gathered at Shiloh to go to war against them.
      comments: []
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: 'The Israelites of the ten western tribes sent a delegation to the
        tribes of Reuben, Gad, and East Manasseh in the land of Gilead. They sent
        Phineas [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> son of Eleazar the priest,
        together with ten respected clan leaders, princes from each of their ten
        tribes. '
      comments:
      - number: "22:13\u201314"
        content: "  Phineas, the grandson of Aaron, was known for his zeal for  in
          resisting apostasy. See  ;  . The name    means \u201Cmouth of brass [judgment].\u201D    "
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: 'The Israelites of the ten western tribes sent a delegation to the
        tribes of Reuben, Gad, and East Manasseh in the land of Gilead. They sent
        Phineas [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> son of Eleazar the priest,
        together with ten respected clan leaders, princes from each of their ten
        tribes. '
      comments:
      - number: "22:13\u201314"
        content: "  Phineas, the grandson of Aaron, was known for his zeal for  in
          resisting apostasy. See  ;  . The name    means \u201Cmouth of brass [judgment].\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So they came to the people in the land of Gilead, to the tribes of
        Reuben, Gad, and East Manasseh. Phineas and the men with him said, '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CWe speak to you on behalf of all <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        people. Why did you rebel against <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> and build
        this altar for yourselves? Why did you quit following the God of Israel and
        do such an evil thing? "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Haven\u2019t we had enough trouble from the terrible sin [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> we committed at Peor? There a plague came upon us even though
        we belong to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. To this day, our conscience is
        stained and we still suffer  from our atrocious deeds. "
      comments:
      - number: 22:17
        content: "  Or \u201CWas that sin too little for us?\u201D The implication
          is that building an altar to any god other than  would be worse than the
          sin the Israelites committed at Peor, which released an epidemic that killed
          twenty-four thousand. See  .    means \u201Copening.\u201D Their sin at
          Peor became an opening for darkness and sickness among them. Peor was the
          mountain where Balak attempted to entice Balaam to pronounce a curse upon
          Israel. See  .      Or \u201Cwe have yet to cleanse ourselves.\u201D This
          statement shows the depth to which their sin had rooted itself in the conscience
          of the nation.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'How dare you turn back from following <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!
        If you rebel against him today, he will be angry with everyone in Israel
        tomorrow. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: 22:18
        content: "  They were asserting that the altar constituted a rebellion against
          God and against the unity of the nation which was to worship  at Shiloh.
          The centralization of the worship of God\u2019s people was at stake. Collective
          guilt can be a \u201Cplague\u201D on the moral conscience of a nation.    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "If you think your land is defiled, then come back to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        land, where his tabernacle stands at Shiloh. But don\u2019t rebel against
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> or us by building for yourself an altar. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: Reconciliation of the Tribes'
      title: Reconciliation of the Tribes
      number: 20
      content: "Don\u2019t forget what happened to Achan! <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        told us, \u2018Destroy everything in the city of Jericho.\u2019 But Achan
        son of Zerah did not obey <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s command regarding
        the devoted things, and so <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> punished us all.
        Achan died because of what he did, and so did many other Israelites because
        of Achan\u2019s sin.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'The Reubenites, the Gadites, and the half-tribe of Manasseh answered
        the princes of the tribes of Israel: '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> is the God of all gods! <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        is the God of all gods! We appeal to God Almighty as our witness. He knows
        why we did this, and we want you to know too! If we rebelled or betrayed
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, then you may take our lives today. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'But we built this altar with no intention of burning any kind of
        sacrifices [[COMMENT(0)]] on it. If we built this altar in rebellion against
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> or to break our covenant with him, then may
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> himself punish us. '
      comments:
      - number: 22:23
        content: "  Or \u201Cburnt sacrifices, grain offerings, or peace offerings.\u201D
          The evident intention of listing these three types of sacrifice is to be
          comprehensive.    "
    - name: '24-25: '
      title: 
      number: 24-25
      content: "No! We love  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>! We were afraid that in
        the future your descendants will say [[COMMENT(0)]] to our descendants, \u2018Who
        are you? What right do you have to worship <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel? He has placed the Jordan River as a barrier between our
        people and your people. You Reubenites and Gadites have no part in the worship
        of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019 And your descendants may prevent
        ours from worshiping him. "
      comments:
      - number: "22:24\u201325"
        content: '  When we are afraid of what people will say, we are walking in
          fear, not faith. This entire episode could have been prevented if the two
          and a half tribes had consulted with the others beforehand.    '
    - name: '24-25: '
      title: 
      number: 24-25
      content: "No! We love  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>! We were afraid that in
        the future your descendants will say [[COMMENT(0)]] to our descendants, \u2018Who
        are you? What right do you have to worship <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel? He has placed the Jordan River as a barrier between our
        people and your people. You Reubenites and Gadites have no part in the worship
        of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019 And your descendants may prevent
        ours from worshiping him. "
      comments:
      - number: "22:24\u201325"
        content: '  When we are afraid of what people will say, we are walking in
          fear, not faith. This entire episode could have been prevented if the two
          and a half tribes had consulted with the others beforehand.    '
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'We did build an altar, but not for burning sacrifices or making offerings. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "We built this altar to show to our people and to your people and
        to the generations to come that we will worship <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        at his tabernacle. We will bring all our offerings into <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        presence there so that your children may never say to our children in the
        future, \u2018You have no part in the worship of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "We have decided among us that if that day should ever come, our descendants
        would reply: \u2018See the replica of the altar of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        which our fathers made here at the border between us\u2014not for burnt offerings
        or sacrifices, [[COMMENT(0)]] but as a witness that we both serve the same
        God.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 22:28
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Far be it from us to rebel against <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        or to turn away from following him this day by building an altar on which
        to present offerings or make sacrifices to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        our God. We would never build an altar to take the place of the altar which
        stands before his tabernacle, the place of his presence.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'When Phineas the priest, and the princes of the tribes heard the
        explanation of the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and East Manasseh, they were satisfied. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Phineas son of Eleazar the priest said to them, \u201CNow we know
        that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> is among us! Since you have not rebelled
        against him, you have indeed saved the Israelites from <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        punishment.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'Then Phineas and the ten princes of the western tribes returned to
        the land of Canaan and told the people of Israel everything that happened. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'The outcome pleased the Israelites and they praised God. They spoke
        no more of going to war against the eastern tribes to destroy the land where
        they had lived. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "The Reubenites and the Gadites called the altar Witness, for they
        said, \u201CThe altar stands as a witness to us all that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        is God.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 22:34
        content: '  How soon we forget all that God has accomplished for us! In a
          little over four centuries, the meaning of the altar of witness had been
          forgotten. See  .  '
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Joshua\u2019s Farewell at Shiloh"
      title: "Joshua\u2019s Farewell at Shiloh"
      number: 1
      content: 'Many years had passed since <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had given
        Israel rest [[COMMENT(0)]] from all their enemies, and Joshua was very old.   '
      comments:
      - number: 23:1
        content: '  See  ;  . Jesus brings us into the faith-rest life.      This
          was about twenty-five years later. Joshua was one hundred and ten when
          he made a final speech to the nation. As Jacob had blessed his sons (see 
          ) and Moses the people (see  ), so Joshua gave a final speech before he
          died.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "So Joshua called together all the Israelites, including all their
        leaders\u2014elders, judges, and officials\u2014and told them, \u201CI\u2019m
        now very old and don\u2019t have much longer to live. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God has shown you his power and
        fought against your enemies for you. You have seen all the wonders that he
        has done to all these nations because he loves you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "See, I have assigned to your tribes all the land from the Jordan
        River in the east to the Mediterranean Sea in the west. I have given you
        the land of all the nations that we\u2019ve already conquered as an inheritance,
        and also the land of those nations that we\u2019ve yet to conquer. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God will absolutely keep his promises
        to you. He will drive out all your enemies and make them retreat before you
        so that you will possess their land. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'So be very strong and steadfast; be careful to obey fully what is
        written in the Scroll [[COMMENT(0)]] of the teaching of Moses, without deviating
        from it.   '
      comments:
      - number: 23:6
        content: "  Singular, not \u201CScrolls,\u201D which shows that Moses was
          the author of the Torah and that it is one book in five parts, a five-fold
          expression of God\u2019s instruction to Israel.      Or \u201Cturning aside
          from it neither to the right nor to the left.\u201D See  ;  ;  . This signifies
          being steadfast in following God\u2019s Word.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Do not intermingle with the nations that are left among you nor speak
        the names of their gods when you take an oath. And by all means don\u2019t
        worship or pray to them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'As you have done until now, cling tightly to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        for he is your God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has driven out great and powerful nations
        before you! No one was able to withstand you, '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God fights for you as he promised
        he would! That is why just one of you causes a thousand of our enemies to
        run away. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 23:10
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: Above all else, keep watch over your hearts, so as to always love
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 23:11
        content: '  To those under the law of Moses, God is to be loved (see  ),
          and so much more for those who have been set free to follow Jesus Christ,
          our Beloved. Serving God must be based on loving him with all our hearts.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CBut if you ever turn away and make alliances with the nations
        that remain in your midst, and establish friendly relations with them and
        intermarry, "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: then you may be sure that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God will
        no longer drive them out before you. Instead they will become a snare and
        a trap for you! They will be like whips on your backsides and thorns in your
        eyes until you perish from the good land that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        your God has given you. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 23:13
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CNow I am about to go the way of all humanity. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        You know with all your heart and soul that not one promise of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        your God has failed. Without a doubt, every promise he made to us he has
        kept; he has fulfilled them all.   "
      comments:
      - number: 23:14
        content: "  Or \u201CI am going the way of everything earthly.\u201D Joshua
          realized his mortality and knew he didn\u2019t have much longer to live.
          See  .      See  .  "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Just as he has kept every wonderful promise he ever made to you,
        so <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God will carry out every threat and
        will obliterate you completely from this good land which he has given you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "If you break the covenant our God, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        made with you and worship other gods and bow down to them, his anger will
        blaze against you. He will punish you, and he will remove you from the face
        of this good land he has given you.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Renewal of the Covenant at Shechem'
      title: Renewal of the Covenant at Shechem
      number: 1
      content: "Joshua assembled all Israel\u2019s tribes at Shechem. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> He summoned all the leaders\u2014elders, judges, and officials
        of Israel\u2014and they all stood in the presence of God. "
      comments:
      - number: 24:1
        content: "  Three locations in the promised land were of vital interest to
          Israel: Gilgal, Shiloh, and Shechem. Gilgal was their military headquarters
          during the invasion. For the believer today, Gilgal represents our beginning,
          our resurrection into new life, and our responsibilities and battles that
          come with it (see  ;  ). Gilgal was also a place of recovery and renewal,
          for the reproach of Egypt was rolled away at Gilgal. Shiloh was the pre-Jerusalem
          capitol and worship center for Israel, the spiritual pivot of national
          life. That is where God had manifested his grace, guidance, and power.
          It represents the holy realm of worship and devotion to God, where we receive
          divine revelation. Shechem was the political cradle of the nation due to
          its importance in the lives of the patriarchs. Shechem was not only the
          geographic center of Canaan but also the moral heart of the nation. At
          this city Abraham built the first altar to  within the land, and here God
          appeared to him and promised that Abraham\u2019s seed would inherit the
          promises (see  ). It is the place of building altars, renewing our covenant-love
          of God (see  ), and receiving our spiritual inheritance as sons and daughters
          of God.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Then Joshua said to them all: \u201CThis is what <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        the God of Israel has to say to you: \u2018Long ago, your forefathers\u2014Terah,
        father of Abraham and father of Nahor\u2014lived beyond the Euphrates and
        worshiped other gods. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'I took your father Abraham from that land and led him through all
        the land of Canaan. I gave him a son, Isaac, and through Isaac I multiplied
        his descendants. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'I gave Isaac two sons, Jacob and Esau. To Esau and his descendants
        I gave the hill country of Edom [[COMMENT(0)]] as their inheritance, while
        Jacob and his family went down to Egypt. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:4
        content: "  Or \u201CSeir.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'When the time of their captivity was complete, I sent Moses and Aaron
        to Egypt to deliver them. I struck the land with great plagues, and afterward
        I led you [[COMMENT(0)]] out from there. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:5
        content: "  In vv.    the author alternates between using \u201Cyour forefathers
          [ancestors]\u201D and \u201Cyou [plural]\u201D as a way of reminding the
          people of that generation that they were included in the redemptive history
          of their people.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'I freed your forefathers from Egypt and brought you to the Red Sea,
        but the Egyptians pursued them with chariots and horsemen. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Then our people cried out to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> for help,
        and he put a thick, dark cloud between you and the Egyptians. When the Egyptians
        attempted to follow them, I caused the sea to roll over them and drown them.
        You saw with your own eyes what I did to the Egyptians. Then you lived in
        the desert for many years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: I brought you to the land of the Amorites, who lived east of the Jordan.
        When they fought against you, I gave them into your hands. As you advanced,
        I gave you victory over them, and you took possession of their land.
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u2018Later, when Balak son of Zippor, king of Moab, opposed Israel,
        he sent for the prophet Balaam son of Beor to come and curse you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: But I refused to listen to Balaam. Instead he had to prophesy my blessings
        over you! I rescued you from his power. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 24:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cfrom his hand.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u2018Later, after you crossed the Jordan miraculously, you faced
        another impossibility\u2014Jericho! The lords of Jericho, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        as well as the Amorites, Perizzites, Canaanites, Hittites, Girgashites, Hivites,
        and Jebusites, fought with you, but I gave you victory over them all! "
      comments:
      - number: 24:11
        content: "  \u201CThe lords of Jericho\u201D may be a reference to the spiritual
          powers (principalities) that held Jericho and the other city-states in
          their grip. Joshua battled not only against flesh and blood but also against
          principalities and powers ().    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'I sent the hornet [[COMMENT(0)]] ahead of you to run off the two
        Amorite kings.  Your weapons and strength had nothing to do with it! '
      comments:
      - number: 24:12
        content: "  See  ;  . The hornet is likely an idiomatic expression for being
          thrown into a panic. One can get a picture of a man thrashing at a swarm
          of hornets trying to sting him. That is the word picture here. As God\u2019s
          presence invaded the land, it brought panic into the hearts of God\u2019s
          enemies.      That is, Og and Sihon. See  .    "
    - name: '13: Choose Whom You Will Serve'
      title: Choose Whom You Will Serve
      number: 13
      content: "I gave you land on which you had not labored and cities that you
        had not built. You are now living in the land I gave you. You are eating
        grapes from vines that others planted and olives from trees planted by the
        people who lived there before you.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CNow therefore, worship <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> with holy
        awe [[COMMENT(0)]] and serve him in authentic love and loyalty. Remove from
        your hearts every false god to whom your fathers bowed down beyond the Euphrates
        and in Egypt and serve <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. "
      comments:
      - number: 24:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cfear\u201D or \u201Creverential honor.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "If it seems wrong in your eyes to serve <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        then make your decision today which gods you will worship\u2014the gods which
        your ancestors worshiped in Mesopotamia or the gods which the Amorites worship
        in the land where you are now living\u2014but I and my family, we will give
        our lives to worship and serve <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 24:15
        content: "  The Septuagint adds the clause \u201Cfor he is holy!\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "The people responded enthusiastically: \u201CFar be it from us to
        abandon <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> and serve other gods! "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Our God, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, set us and our fathers free
        from slavery in the land of Egypt, the house of bondage. He performed these
        many great signs and wonders before our eyes. <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> 
        supernaturally protected us throughout our entire journey as we passed through
        the territory of other nations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "And as we advanced, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> powerfully drove
        out from before us all the people, including the Amorites who inhabited the
        country. Yes, Joshua! We, too, will worship and serve <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        for he alone is our God.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Joshua warned the people, \u201CDon\u2019t be so quick to say, \u2018We
        will worship and serve <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>.\u201D</smallcaps>
        for he is a holy God. And he will tolerate no rivals.  God will not forgive
        the sin of unfaithfulness to him.   "
      comments:
      - number: 24:19
        content: "  Or \u201CYou will not be able to serve        Or \u201CHe is
          El, the Jealous.\u201D See  ;  ;  .      Or \u201CHe will not forgive your
          transgressions and your sins.\u201D Joshua possibly knew that they were
          secretly practicing idolatry.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "If after <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has been gracious to you,
        you turn and forsake him to worship other gods, then he will turn and deal
        harshly with you and totally consume you!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CNo, no!\u201D the people responded. \u201CWe promise to worship
        and serve <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Then Joshua said to them, \u201CYou are witnesses against yourselves
        that you have chosen to serve <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D\u201CYes,
        we are witnesses,\u201D they responded."
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CNow then,\u201D said Joshua, \u201Cthrow away these foreign
        gods that are among you, and yield your hearts fully to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        the God of Israel!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "And the people promised Joshua, \u201CWe really will worship and
        serve our God, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, and listen to his voice.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'On that day when the people were gathered at Shechem, Joshua made
        a covenant between them and <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, which contained
        laws the people were to obey. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Joshua recorded all this in a book of divine instruction. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Then he set up a large stone memorial at the tent pole  near the holy place
        of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:26
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe book of the law of God.\u201D It is difficult to
          identify this as any particular book included in the Old Testament.     
          Or \u201Coak tree [terebinth].\u201D This is a hapax legomenon that Rabbinical
          Judaism interprets as \u201Cpole.\u201D (See A. Cohen,  , xl, pp. 160ff).    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Joshua said to all the people, \u201CLook at this stone! It will
        serve as a witness, for it heard all the words that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        spoke to us; [[COMMENT(0)]] it will be a witness against you if you rebel
        against our God.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 24:27
        content: '  The stones (inanimate objects) can hear our words.    '
    - name: '28: Joshua and Eleazar Buried in the Promised Land'
      title: Joshua and Eleazar Buried in the Promised Land
      number: 28
      content: Joshua then dismissed the people, each to their own inheritance.
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Some time later, Joshua son of Nun, the servant of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>,\u201D a title that had been used exclusively for
        Moses up to this point in the book of Joshua.</smallcaps> died at the age
        of one hundred and ten. "
      comments:
      - number: 24:29
        content: "  Finally upon his death Joshua was called \u201Cthe servant of      "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'They buried him on his own property, at Timnath Serah [[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the hill country of Ephraim, north of Mount Gaash.   '
      comments:
      - number: 24:30
        content: "  Or \u201CTimnath Heres.\u201D See    and first footnote.       
          means \u201Cshaking\u201D or \u201Ccommotion.\u201D    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: Israel was faithful to serve <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> during
        the lifetime of Joshua and the lifetime of the elders who lived on after
        Joshua, those who had experienced all the miracles that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        had done for Israel. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 24:31
        content: '  See  ,  .    '
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "They buried Joseph\u2019s bones, which the Israelites had brought
        up from Egypt, at Shechem, in the tract of land that Jacob bought for a hundred
        pieces of silver [[COMMENT(0)]] from the children of Hamor, Shechem\u2019s
        father.  So the land became the inheritance of Joseph\u2019s descendants. "
      comments:
      - number: 24:32
        content: "  Or \u201Cfor a hundred qesitah,\u201D an unknown unit of money.     
          See  . The Septuagint adds \u201CThere they deposited in his grave the
          flint knives used to circumcise the children of Israel at Gilgal, as the
          Lord commanded them when he brought them out of Egypt.\u201D    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'The chief priest  [[COMMENT(0)]] Eleazar son of Aaron also died.
        They buried him on the hill  of his son Phineas, which had been assigned
        to him in Ephraim. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:33
        content: "  The words \u201Cchief priest\u201D are found in some Syriac manuscripts
          and the Septuagint.      Or \u201CGibeah.\u201D    is the common Hebrew
          word for \u201Chill.\u201D      The Septuagint adds, \u201CAt that time,
          the children of Israel took up the ark of God and carried it about among
          them.\u201D  "
